For several days now, we have been living in pain, in confusion, in a painful sense of helplessness that makes us fragile, vulnerable, disoriented, and above all, deeply saddened. For there is nothing more contagious than the pain of innocent men, women, old people and children. The horror of innocent humans brutally torn from their loved ones, beaten, imprisoned, tortured and diabolically terrorized is something that tears at the heart of anyone with a heart capable of beating for their fellow man. As parents, how can we not put ourselves in the shoes of those parents whose children's fate is unknown to them! As human beings, how can we not feel the dramatic echo of so much suffering! As human beings, where can we find hope, optimism, joy of life, when so much of our unfortunate humanity can go? Yet each of us knows in his conscience that every conflict, from the most trivial to the most bitter, is always and only an intellectual accident. We all know the weapons with which we could avoid their tragic consequences. What prevents us from using them? As people of faith, we pray with all our hearts that this will end as soon as possible; that everyone will be able to reunite with their loved ones and return to their homes. Let us pray. Let us pray with contrite hearts, with consistency and intensity, hoping in our hearts that this will end soon.

THE LONG ROAD OF THE THREE ABRAHAM This photograph taken in 1999, when I was reporting for National Geographic on the founding father of the three religions Abraham, has a special story. In the context of absolute horror, does this image demonstrate a misplaced angelism when everything is chaos, violence, terrorism, carnage, hatred, terror? I remain convinced that we must still and always, and more today than before, work for this semblance of peace. If we don't believe in even a little glimmer of light, then we give up. We have a commitment to the present and future generations. THE STORY BEHIND THIS PHOTOGRAPH There is a land, so close to our own, where Christians, Jews and Muslims live. Over there, children are often raised without any comprehension of the other‚Äôs religions. As the most ancient texts attest, Abraham is a founding father of all three of these religions, a father whose children are in conflict with each other. I was doing a reportage on Abraham for National Geographic, his journey, his history, and his legacy. As a symbol of peace, I sought out three children from each of these religions: the Christian boy was named Abraham, the Jewish boy, Avram, and the Muslim boy, Ibrahim. While the first name is a common one, I nevertheless had no end of difficulties getting these three children together. The obstacles facing our meeting ranged from religious festivals, roadblocks, and the refusal of a homeowner to admit a child of another faith cross the threshold of his home in order to pose for a photo on his terrace. Indeed, my idealistic concept, based upon a desire for peace, faced many challenges before it became a reality. One day, three children whose memories of a land and a father could unite them, but whom everything separates, managed to meet for a moment to pose for a photograph. Ibrahim, Avram and Abraham made the lost message of peace from their namesake live again, if only for that brief time. These three children, bearing the name of Abraham, posed in front of the Dome of the Rock and the Wailing Wall. One must not give up, this photo is proof. Since 1999, when I did this reportage on Abraham for National Geographic, I have continued to pursue my visual quest throughout the world for that which brings us together, even at a time when only division is evoked in the name of God #peace #paix #israel #palestine

The Struggle to Come Out From the World by J.C. Ryle To come out from the world is not an easy thing. It cannot be easy so long as human nature is what it is, and a busy devil is always near us. It requires a constant struggle and exertion; it entails incessant conflict and self-denial; it often places us in exact opposition to members of our own families, friends and neighbors; it sometimes obliges us to do things which give great offence, and bring on us ridicule and petty persecution. It is precisely this which makes many hang back and shrink from decided religion. They know they are not right; they know that they are not so ‚Äúthorough‚Äù in Christ‚Äôs service as they ought to be, and they feel uncomfortable and ill at ease. But the fear of man keeps them back. And so they linger on through life with aching, dissatisfied hearts, ‚Äì with too much religion to be happy in the world, and too much of the world to be happy in their religion. If the truth were known, I fear this is a very common case.

I think there's just too much pressure that people put on the word Love. Like it's just supposed to solve everything. Like it's a cure all to every problem and that just by saying "I love you" everything magically becomes okay. But then why do so many of us look for someone else to talk to when something goes wrong? Why do we seek out someone who maybe be more willing to listen to what we are going through and give us advice? Why do we want someone who understands what we are going through rather than just someone who tells us they love us? It's so hard to be one person, now imagine what it's like having to deal with all the emotions of two. And maybe that's why people are always so unsure about love. Why things go down hill so often when there is a fight. Why they run away from any kind of conflict. And why we seek out the company of old friends who have known us for a while to sit with and talk to. It's hard to open up to someone and harder still when it's about something that scares you. And I know love scares you. Losing someone you care about scares you. Which is why sometimes just being understanding of someone's emotions, of their fears, of what they are going through in life is enough. Friends who share memes are sometimes even more appreciated that one's who share love notes. Because sometimes, understanding is just better than love. __ scene by @artalanche_ridhigupta for The Scribbled Stories

Sin will be rampant everywhere, and the love of many will grow cold.  But the one who endures to the end will be saved.‚Äù (Matthew 24:6-13)  

The first thing I notice about this passage is the command of ‚Äúdon‚Äôt panic.‚Äù Our job as Christians is to not be caught up with the rest of the world with the spirit of fear. ‚ÄúGod has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.‚Äù (2 Tim. 1:7)  The second thing I notice about this passage is Jesus telling us when we hear of ‚Äúwars and rumors of wars‚Äù that ‚Äúthe end won‚Äôt follow immediately.‚Äù We might be living in the end times, but this is not the end of the end according to Jesus.  The third thing I notice here is Jesus‚Äô stern warning against false prophets.  It‚Äôs easy when there is fear and turmoil to cling to words that make us feel good, but they may not necessarily be what the Bible says.  Beware of false teachers, be grounded in the word of God.  This is no time to follow popular opinions.  This is a time to stand on God‚Äôs word.

So what's our assignment as Christians?
Jesus says in Luke 19:13, "Occupy until I come." The end times are not a time to sit on your rapture rug and wait until Jesus comes back. The end times are for a glorious church to rise and to rule and reign with Christ as "kings and priests unto our God." (Rev. 1:6) Now is the time to take our royal authority over the darkness, to push back the darkness, to contend for souls, to go to war with our prayers and spiritual weapons. Jesus is not coming back for a weak bride. Jesus is coming back for a warrior bride. Now is the time to take authority over the darkness and to push back the gates of hell with our prayers.

So when you hear of wars and rumors of wars, don't panic. Jesus said this is not the end of the end. Occupy until Christ comes. Push back the gates of hell with your prayers and weapons of warfare. Stand on the word and sound doctrine. And remember your prayers are more powerful than you realize. They can pull down the demonic strongholds in the earth, which in turn changes the physical realm. When we go after the kingdom of hell in prayer, we will begin to see the victory in the physical realm as well. Pray for Israel. Pray for the nations of the world. Pray bold prayers and take authority over the dark powers and demons. Christ gave you that authority. The church is the hope of the world. "Upon this rock I will build my church, and all the powers of hell will not conquer it." (Matt. 16:18)

#emotional aspects of Arthritis, Bronchitis, Headaches, Frozen shoulder and Insomnia! Often, tuning into and recognizing the thoughts, emotions and attitudes which have contributed to the problem can begin your healing process. This is 1. Because when you acknowledge what has been suppressed you begin the process of release. And 2. Awareness - equals choice. Choice gives you an opportunity to reflect on your life, become aware of what does not work and potentially change it. Healing encompasses every aspect of your being, including your physical health and fitness, emotional wellbeing, mental attitude, energetic welfare, spiritual wisdom and strength. It is important to recognize that your body (including finer bodies, soul and spirit) is not your enemy; but a messenger which can help you to know yourself more fully. Here are some ailments and what can potentially cause them. Arthritis ‚Äì holding onto anger and resentment from the past. Carrying guilt, remorse and shame. Difficulty in forgiving self and others. Complaining about life; worrying, but not wanting to make changes. Feeling stuck and limited. (Has to start working on inner openness and flexibility!) Bronchitis ‚Äì feeling too much pressure. Conflict and anger in the family, which leads to irritation with people close to you. Blaming others for what you can‚Äôt fix or control. Needing time out and time to yourself. Feeling a lack of appreciation and love. Pushing people away. (Need to develop healthy boundaries and take time for self!) Headaches ‚Äì stress, overwhelm, tiredness, seriousness, too much going on. Feeling out of control. Self criticism, judgment, invalidation, self sabotage. Too much thinking and analysis. Overcrowded, frustrated, undermined. (Need to learn how to be more objective and more grounded!) Frozen shoulder ‚Äì suppressing your feelings. Experiencing too much strain, stress and worry. Not dealing with your challenges ‚Äò numbing‚Äô them. Feeling stuck, trying to control rather than allow. Fear of the future. Wanting to give up. Feeling like a failure. Engulfed by problems. A relentless barrage of rockets has left hundreds of thousands of people displaced, and it has also had a profound impact on many animals, leaving them terrified and traumatized. Those who have survived this harrowing attack are desperately searching for their families, scraps of food, and a safe place to hide. Our partner, Let The Animals Live (LTAL), is an organization operating a shelter and clinic in Ashkelon, Israel's major port city, which has regrettably been a repeated target of Hamas rocket attacks. To date, LTAL has successfully evacuated 32 sick and injured dogs and cats from war-torn Ashkelon to their shelter located in Kfar Ruth, central Israel. LTAL, in collaboration with veterinarians and essential supplies, is heading south to provide aid to animals in need. While some areas may be inaccessible, your generous donations will support the provision of crucial supplies to dedicated volunteers. These animals are frightened, starving, and in dire need of YOUR support. We are extremely saddened to report that 'Dada', one of the adult lionesses of the Marsh Pride, was most likely a victim of Human-Wildlife Conflict (HWC) recently. Early in the month, Governors' Camp guides noticed an open wound in her side and although she was found relaxing with her cubs and appeared to be somewhat unaffected by her injury, the scenario was definitely cause for concern. We alerted the vets from the Sheldrick Wildlife Trust (SWT) who are based at the Mara Research Station inside the National Reserve. They responded and met us at Governors‚Äô Camp and from there we led them to the pride. Dada was darted and the pride quickly dispersed, with two of the females carefully leading her two young cubs away. It was about 15 minutes before the anaesthetic took its full effect on Dada and because she was darted amongst thick vegetation, we had to pull her out into the open. Anaesthesia lasts only one hour; so that meant there was just 45 minutes remaining. Dr Njoroge of SWT worked fast and efficiently to clean, disinfect and suture the wound, leaving a small opening for drainage. Antibiotics were also administered. After about 20 minutes, Dada was given a reversal agent to wake up. After looking around for some time, she pulled herself up and began calling for her cubs - thankfully she was reunited with them soon after. The following morning we found her and the rest of the pride feeding on a buffalo that they had taken down during the night. Dada is expected to make a full recovery and we thank Dr Njoroge and his team for treating her. Incidents like this are sadly becoming more and more frequent and are very concerning and upsetting for all involved. It is important to note that Governors' Camp has no official mandate that allows us to actively protect these lions (or any other wildlife) and that unfortunately, there is very little by way of monitoring that we can provide for these lions, during the night. We therefore focus on other ways of mitigating HWC such as community education and outreach programs, sponsoring the salaries for Lion Ambassadors, covering the costs of a lion collar and donating predator deterrent lights. We are of course truly saddened by this event that is no doubt distressing for a mother lion and her cubs and so we are actively working as a team to see what more we can do. Image credits Frankie Adamson.

As western media outlets emphasize the tragic loss of 40 innocent Israeli children, they should uphold impartiality by also covering the devastating deaths of 260 innocent Palestinian children in recent days. Additionally, it's crucial for them to shed light on the distressing fact that, since 2000, over 2,300 Palestinian children have lost their lives due to actions by Israeli forces and settlers. By not doing so, a concerning bias is apparent, hindering a comprehensive understanding of the conflict's human impact and perpetuating a skewed narrative. By giving prominence to the deaths of one group of children, it implicitly conveys a message about the perceived value of the lives of the others. In striving for fair and comprehensive reporting, media outlets play a critical role in shaping public understanding of complex conflicts like the Israeli-Palestinian struggle. The tragedy of innocent lives lost knows no boundaries, and every child's death is a heart-wrenching event that warrants equal attention and empathy, regardless of their nationality or origin. By providing a balanced account of the human toll, media can help foster a more informed and empathetic global discourse, encouraging dialogue and ultimately contributing to a path of understanding and peace amidst this longstanding conflict. The responsibility lies not only in reporting the facts but also in acknowledging and valuing every life affected by the strife, nurturing a narrative of compassion and humanity. Furthermore, in the pursuit of balanced journalism, if the media is committed to interviewing Palestinian leaders and questioning their stance on condemning attacks on Israel, it is imperative for them to exhibit the same level of due diligence by posing analogous inquiries to Israeli authorities. Asking Israeli authorities whether they condemn the killing of innocent civilians in Palestine and the longstanding system of apartheid is essential to ensure a fair and unbiased representation of perspectives. Such symmetry in questioning helps foster an equitable narrative that considers the views and actions of all parties involved, encouraging a more comprehensive understanding of the complex issues at hand.

Some important context on Israel/Palestine, from @RedPrecariat: "I see a lot of socialists pointing out that Israel 'created' Hamas. While there is truth to that, it's reductionist and counterproductive to bring up in most cases when discussing this conflict with people. The rise of religious nationalism within the Palestinian movement was driven by two key and connected events: 1) Gorbachev coming to power. 2) The Oslo Accords. As we all know, the USSR had been the patron of many liberation movements around the world, including the leftist-secular PLO. When Gorbachev came to power, that changed. The USSR slowly started to cut support for the PLO and pressured Arafat to recognize Israel and start negotiating. This all came to a head with the August Coup, which the PLO sympathized with. As a result, the USSR cut all support for the PLO, causing it to dissolve months later. The Madrid Conference, which restarted the "peace , kicked off in October of 1991. That date is obviously not a coincidence. This process would culminate in the Oslo Accords in which the PLO recognized Israel and Israel recognized the PLO as Palestine's representative. The vast majority of Palestinians viewed this as a grand betrayal by the PLO, which quickly became a collaborationist organization (at least its leadership did). With the collapse of material and popular support for leftist-secular groups, a power vacuum developed. This vacuum would be filled by Hamas and other similar groups, which received material support from places like Qatar/Egypt. These groups lacked the stink of betrayal that now stuck to the collaborationist PLO. The left had lost its revolutionary drive (except for the PFLP). Israel did try to help this process along for "divide and conquer" reasons, but the reality is that the ascendancy of Hamas was part of a much larger historical process in Palestine and the rest of the Arab/Islamic world. So why does it matter if we reductively argue that "Israel created Hamas?" It matters because doing so means we're playing into the Zionist framing of Hamas as a terror organization detached from the legitimate will of the Palestinian people. It's NOT a Zionist creation. Hamas is just one organized faction within a larger coalition. The liberation of Palestine is at the core of its ideology, and its Islamism does not prevent it from working with Marxists and non-Muslims to achieve that central goal. The Zionist state wants us on the back foot trying to explain why we support "evil Muslim terrorists" because it distracts us from the core point that Israel is a genocidal apartheid state and an imperial outpost of the Anglo-American hegemon. Don't qualify your solidarity with the Palestinian struggle by wringing your hands over Hamas. Solidarity isn't about friendship or having the exact same beliefs.. it's about the recognition of our common struggle against exploitative and oppressive structures."

Narcissists, characterised by their extreme self-centeredness and lack of empathy, possess a manipulative storytelling tendency that often vilifies those they have wronged. By strategically crafting narratives that depict their victims as the instigators of conflict or as morally flawed individuals, narcissists cunningly avoid facing the consequences of their own harmful actions. This intriguing behavioural pattern demonstrates their steadfast commitment to preserving their self-image and shielding themselves from any accountability. When confronted with their destructive behaviour, narcissists quickly resort to distorting the truth by transforming themselves into the innocent party and painting their victims as villains. With carefully chosen words and skilful manipulation, they effectively shift the blame onto others, safeguarding their self-perceived moral superiority. They skillfully use emotional manipulation techniques to undermine the credibility of those who dare to challenge their actions, leaving them in a situation where their voice is silenced, and their character is assassinated. Unfortunately, this deceptive storytelling has severe consequences for the victims of narcissists. Their reputation becomes tarnished, their grievances invalidated, and their pain dismissed. The narcissist, expertly manipulating the narrative, creates an alternate reality where their actions are justified, and their victims are undeserving of sympathy or understanding. This perpetuates a cycle of emotional abuse, as the victim becomes further marginalised and isolated from supportive networks due to the fabricated tales spun by the narcissist. It is essential to recognise the manipulative tactics employed by narcissists. By promoting awareness and education, we can help victims regain control over their own stories and expose the narcissist's attempts at self-preservation. It is through knowledge and solidarity that the truth can triumph over the distorted tales woven by narcissistic individuals. Do you teach students how to solve conflicts in a healthy way? It's such an important skill that will benefit them throughout their lives. As they are learning and developing this skill, it can be helpful to teach kids the "3 C's" of conflict resolution: Calm down, Communicate, and Choose a solution. üß† Calm Down: Conflict with others can bring up some intense emotions. When this happens, it's hard to think clearly or make good choices. That's why the first step is to calm down. Taking a break, doing some deep breathing, or talking to someone can help kids (and adults) feel more calm so they are ready to handle the issue at hand. üí¨ Communicate: This is the part of conflict resolution where the two parties calmly talk about the problem. Each person can share their perspective and listen to what the other person has to say. This is also a great time to apologize if needed. üí° Choose A Solution: Once everyone has had a chance to share their perspective, and to listen to others, it's time to figure out how to solve the problem. The solution will depend on the problem, but some examples include taking turns, finding a compromise, or sharing. Hey, Hivemind -- Do you know how much I like and appreciate you? I hope you do. This group is amazing: people from diverse backgrounds, homeschooling for dozens of different reasons, holding different views in politics, religion, and worldviews come together every day to discuss homeschooling topics in a reasoned, civil, decent way. I rarely have to chide anyone for ad hominem attacks. I rarely find cause to delete anything. It's a little bumpy now and again, but for the most part, you guys are the cat's pajamas, and I love you for it. Years ago, on my local, secular homeschool group, a dad joined and started posting these wild religious posts.* I asked him to stop and said he was plenty welcome to post, "I wrote this [short description of content], if you're interested, it's [url] over here." He came back spittin' mad and asked who I thought I was. I responded that I was, in fact, the group owner, that he'd agreed to the group rules when he joined, and that he didn't have to stay if he didn't want to follow them. Over my shoulder Kidlet quipped, "And I have a pink hoodie!" Thus was born the family joke that a pink hoodie is a symbol of great power. I take that power very seriously: and I loathe having to use it. I joined this organization *because* it supports homeschooling in WA. All homeschoolers in WA. That's part of what makes WHO unique and amazing. To be frank, I did not anticipate the coordinated onslaught from from the Banned Books Week post -- I really just love discussing literature: it was one of my most favourite parts of homeschooling. Until yesterday, in 13 years I had banned five people from this list -- that's how important I think that WHO is to homeschoolers. I hate to do it, and I never do it lightly. Five people in over a decade. Yesterday, I banned-and-deleted 314. These people are not homeschoolers, are not part of our community, and do not want to do anything other than create conflict. They were largely from Texas, Florida***, Missouri, and Iowa, and, as you saw if you were following that thread, were acting in concert from the playbook of a religious political organization**, with a cherry overlay of name calling. (I've been called an "unfit parent" before for unschooling and allowing my kidlet more freedom than other people are comfortable with, but this is the first time I've been called a pedophile, groomer, or predator (well, technically, I was called a "predater" but I'm going to say that I'm pretty sure (at least in context) this was meant to be "predator." As you might imagine, the offlist messages were worse, and I had a few cyber security people tell me to expect death threats). Please let me know if someone you know was wrongly deleted. At some point late last night, I stopped bothering to look at the posters' info to make sure they weren't from here. I may have caught a few legitimate WA homeschoolers in that dragnet, and like I said: I am loathe to prevent any homeschoolers from accessing this resource. But I'm also not going to let this page devolve into some troll sandbox to play in. Warmly, ~Jen *Amongst other things, he had grand plans to bring Islam, the LDS, and Judaism together to form a single religion. (I try not to judge, but I don't think my characterization here is unwarranted). **Edited to add: I know this because my family was part of that organization when I was growing up. I do not know if the folks yesterday were religious, just noting which playbook they were using. ***Edited to add: WHO has followers who lived here and left (including one board member who headed for a sunnier clime), who live elsewhere and find us through friends, etc. I don't know if the folks who piled on yesterday were religious or not, what their politics were, or even if they were people and not bots. Just noting that there was a pattern (and that none -- not one -- of them were from WA).

We, members of the undersigned human rights organizations in Israel, are shocked and horrified in these dreadful days. Hamas‚Äô horrific crimes against innocent civilians - including children, women, and the elderly - have shaken us all, and we are struggling to recover from the unbearable sights and sounds. Some of us were in the Israeli communities on the Gaza border during the assault; many of us have family, friends, and colleagues who endured and are still in the midst of the harrowing events; and we all know people who were murdered, injured, or abducted. It will take time to fully understand the implications and consequences of Hamas‚Äô heinous attack, for which there can be no justification. Most of our teams include Israelis and Palestinians; therefore, some of us have relatives and colleagues in Gaza currently living under the ongoing assault of the Israeli military. Children, women, and the elderly are being indiscriminately attacked with nowhere to hide. Even now ‚Äì especially now ‚Äì we must maintain our moral and humane position and refuse to give in to despair or the urge for vengeance. Keeping our faith in the human spirit and its inherent goodness is more vital than ever. One thing is clear: We will never surrender our belief in humanity - even now, when doing so is more challenging than ever. Having always opposed the harming of innocent civilians, it remains our duty in these terrible times - as we count our dead on the Israeli side and worry about wounded, missing, and abducted loved ones, and as bombs are being dropped on residential neighborhoods in Gaza, wiping out entire families with no possibility of burying the dead ‚Äì to raise our voices loud and clear against the harming of all innocent civilians, both in Israel and Gaza. We call for the immediate release of all hostages and an end to the bombardment of civilians in Israel and in Gaza. Humanitarian aid must be allowed to reach civilian populations, medical facilities and places of refuge must not be harmed, and vital resources such as water and electricity must not be cut off. The killing of additional civilians will not bring back those who were lost. Indiscriminate destruction and a siege harming innocents will not bring relief, justice, or calm. As individuals working to promote human rights and who believe in the sanctity of life, we urgently call for an end to all indiscriminate harming of civilian lives and infrastructure. We call for negotiations and all possible action to be taken to bring about the release of the hostages - while prioritizing the civilians held by Hamas. It is the only humane and rational thing to do, and it must be done now. There are no excuses for the horrendous killings and acts committed by Hamas attackers against Israeli civilians at a festival this weekend, nor for the decades-long subjugation and occupation of Palestinians and their lands by Israeli forces. Yet to resolve issues facing us today, we must understand the path that led to this moment. Addressing ‚Äúwhere do we go from here?‚Äù first requires answering ‚Äúhow did we get here?‚Äù In supporting liberation for all oppressed peoples, including our Palestinian and Jewish relatives, we look to history to teach us of the right steps forward. In treaty negotiations with the U.S. government, it is told that Sitting Bull said ‚Äúlet us put our minds together and see what life we can make for our children.‚Äù We heed Sitting Bull‚Äôs wisdom as we pray for healing and an end to violence in Palestine/Israel. Indigenous Peoples intimately understand the broader dynamics in play here. On one hand, we have militarized and nationalistic settler-colonial rule over a subjugated and long-disregarded people. On the other, the settler-colonial enterprise of the Israeli state is itself a product of the deceitful and manipulative dealings of greedy Western powers, then and now. Paradoxically, Israel is a creation of European-Christian imperialism and supremacy, forces that abused Jews for centuries. The majority of the world‚Äôs ‚ÄúZionists‚Äù are actually evangelical Christians who not only regard Jews as antithetical to their worldview of Christ‚Äôs return, but who also are motivated by deep-seated Islamophobia and Arabophobia. During the Holocaust, the countries of Europe and the United States turned away hundreds of thousands of Jews seeking refuge from Nazi gas chambers and firing squads. Many of those Jews were returned to the Nazi death camps for slaughter, and the lucky ones were deported to Palestine (often against their wishes) to prop up an emerging nation-state integral to the geopolitical interests of European powers and the U.S. Without the conniving and calculated efforts of Europe to ‚Äúdivide and conquer‚Äù the Middle East for long-term strategic military and financial gain, the Israeli state would likely not exist. Without the selfish interests of the U.S.‚Äôs sprawling military and fossil fuel industrial complex, Israel would not be able to maintain its settler-colonial rule over Palestine. The old ‚Äúcrabs in a bucket‚Äù analogy is apt here: faced with a conflict between their own survival and the humanity of their Palestinian neighbors, Israel‚Äôs founders chose the former. Driven by white supremacy and racial hierarchy, Western powers were quick to side with the Jews they sought to remove from their own countries over the ‚Äúdesert dwelling‚Äù Arab populations of the Middle East. The early Zionist leaders of the Israeli state embraced these despicable notions in furtherance of their own survival and statehood. Ironically, while prior to 1948, ‚ÄúPalestinian‚Äù included Jewish inhabitants of the Holy Land, who lived, worked, and loved alongside their Arab Muslim and Christian neighbors, Israel‚Äôs founding ruptured that communal solidarity and replaced it with a regime that placed Jews atop all others. None of this diminishes the historic and spiritual Judaic connection to the Land of Israel. Jews have maintained a physical presence in the Holy Land, without interruption, since the destruction of Jerusalem‚Äôs second Holy Temple and their expulsion in 70 C.E. Prior to that, even in periodic times of absence, Jews maintained ties to the Holy Land for nearly 4,000 years. Their language, laws, culture, and ritual practice are all rooted in that land. At the same time, Jews have been compelled over the last 2,000 years to embrace diasporic lifeways. Christian hegemony forced Jews into second-class citizenship, at best. Centuries of pogroms and legalized discrimination across Europe ‚Äî often mandated by the Church ‚Äî kept Jews in a constant position of fear, trauma, and isolation. In just a few years, the Holocaust killed half of the world‚Äôs Jews. Yet it is crucial to highlight that Judaism and Zionism are distinct concepts; many of the world‚Äôs Jews oppose or don‚Äôt consider the Israeli state part of their religious-ethnic outlook. Many Jews consciously chose not to immigrate to Palestine in the 1940s. Others immigrated out of lack of choice. And certainly, many immigrated out of zealous yearning. Nor does the above context negate the ongoing responsibility of the Israeli state to take accountability for its repression and cruelty towards Palestinians. The Holocaust and millennia of antisemitism are no justification for brutal occupation and colonial rule over millions of people. The past victimhood of Jews is improperly weaponized by Israel‚Äôs government and Zionist ideologues to justify victimizing Palestinians. Today‚Äôs Israeli leadership is unmistakably neo-fascist in its repression not just of the Palestinian People, but in its repression of free speech and acceptance of authoritarian governance. For the past few days I‚Äôve been quiet because I was so overwhelmed and worried about being misinterpreted. This morning I‚Äôm filled with a sadness for humanity- that I had to say something. For me this is not about picking a side in Israel/ Palestine. It‚Äôs that as I mourn for my extended family in Israel who I heard has been kidnapped and more civilians who were attacked. I also mourn for the millions of civilians in Gaza and Palestinian Territories, for my loved ones who have family there, for the mothers and fathers who are mourning their children, or who are without food, water, electricity. When we dehumanize a whole people on either side- then it gives permission to do anything and feel nothing. As a 2nd generation Immigrant- descendant of German Jews who escaped Nazi Germany and also descendant of Black South African family who escaped Apartheid South Africa. And as Black American born and raised in The Bay Area, I see this power struggle from so many different angles. And I know it‚Äôs not a fair fight. It‚Äôs painful from every direction right now and in my heart I just can‚Äôt be one sided about it. It‚Äôs never justifiable when children and mothers and civilian families are attacked period. It‚Äôs all of our responsibility to look into the long painful history of this conflict - including myself. It‚Äôs complex and I still don‚Äôt fully understand it. Like everyone, over the last few days I've looked on in horror at the events in Gaza and Israel. Regardless of your political position, the murder of innocent civilians is gut wrenching and wrong, and the Greens condemn those horrific attacks on civilians, whether they are Israeli or Palestinian. The scale of the horror is exactly why I think it‚Äôs crucial we are honest and clear eyed about how to stop this violence. As long as the Israeli government and military continue their occupation of Palestine and brutal blockade of Gaza, this cycle of violence will continue. For 17 years now, the roughly 2.5 million Palestians in Gaza have lived under a brutal blockade enforced by the Israeli Government and military, denying Palestians crucial medicines, construction materials, food, and other essentials. Here‚Äôs what Conservative UK Prime Minister David Cameron said all the way back in 2010: "Everybody knows that we are not going to sort out the problem of the Middle East peace process while there is, effectively, a giant open prison in Gaza." 50% of Gaza‚Äôs population are children under the age of 15 and 97% of water in Gaza is undrinkable. The one power station in Gaza was bombed in 2014, and the Israeli government hasn‚Äôt allowed it to be repaired properly, so Palestians experience power cuts for about 11 hours everyday. It‚Äôs almost impossible to get in or out of Gaza - even if you need urgent medical care. Because the Israeli government has blocked many medical supplies into Gaza, if you are diagnosed with cancer or other serious illnesses, the only chance you have is if you get a special permit to leave Gaza. Israeli authorities regularly deny or seriously delay these applications, which has seen people die of cancer while waiting to be approved. Israel has repeatedly bombed hospitals in Gaza. In response to all this, in 2018/19 Palestinians organised a mass peaceful protest movement in Gaza that saw hundreds of thousands of people march on the border checkpoints that lock Palestinians in Gaza. 150 Palestinians were murdered by the Israeli military in response and 10,000 were injured - over 5000 of whom were shot. Many of those shot were deliberately shot in the knees and ankles, which often led to amputations. Unemployment in Gaza is at 46% and the entire population lives under constant drone surveillance and intermittent bombing by the Israeli military. Studies have found over half of Palestinian children have presented with serious trauma based mental illness as a result of the blockade and bombing. Some Palestinians interviewed in Gaza have been quite clear about not having much to lose, having lost all hope of living a good life. This week, the Israeli Defence Minister has announced that Israel is cutting off all food, electricity, medicine and water into Gaza, while describing Palestinians in Gaza as ‚Äúhuman animals‚Äù. As the Israeli bombing of Gaza escalates, thousands of injured Palestinian civilians, including children, are heading to hospitals without power or supplies. Not only is this an act of genocide, but this will only further accelerate the cycle of violence. It‚Äôs seriously alarming that this week western governments, including Australia, have refused to condemn the Israeli state‚Äôs acts of genocide, or made any moves to prevent Israel from only further escalating this conflict. If we want to achieve peace it would look like an end to the blockade and occupation. Ending the illegal settlements on Palestinian land. A huge, international backed aid and reconstruction program for Palestine, to give Palestinians a future and some hope. This sort of process would bring peace for Israelis and Palestinians, and create conditions for Palestinians and Israelis alike to go on and build a good life. More bombing, blockading and killing will only bring more violence and misery.

text: A CALL TO PRAYER. Praying for peace in times of war can feel like facing a dragon with a paper sword. But we know that is only an illusion. War is not all-powerful, inevitable or unstoppable. Its origins are in the same place as peace: in the human heart. When we pray for peace, we pray to reach the hearts of other human beings, on all sides of the conflict, to restore a sense of compassion and hope. We seek to pour the water of life onto the flames of hate, one person at a time, until the rage subsides. So please, keep praying with me for peace, no matter how tempted you may be to despair. Confront the dragon with your love, as you work in every way you can, for the cause of peace. - Rt Rev Steven Charleston

TOPIC: THE COST OF DISCIPLESHIP Memory Verse: Matthew 10:39 - He that findeth his life shall lose it: and he that loseth his life for my sake shall find it (KJV). Lesson Bible Text: Luke 9:57-62; Matthew 10:34-39; 16:21-27. INTRODUCING THE LESSON The "cost of discipleship" means what it will take one to become Jesus' disciple. Jesus taught that being His disciple comes at a cost. To be His disciple requires a clear and total commitment and will involve sacrifice, suffering and service. When Jesus started recruiting His disciples, many initially are willing to follow the Lord, but fail to count the cost. Upon realizing the great sacrifice necessary to follow Him, many are unwilling to pay the price. For anyone to embark on a project he or she must sit down to consider the cost of it. Likewise, we must consider the cost of following Jesus before we can follow Him. We must count the cost and be willing to pay the price in service to the Lord. When we commit our entire lives to Jesus as His disciples, we emulate the One who laid down His life on our behalf for our salvation. 1. BE WHOLLY DEVOTED TO CHRIST A. Noble Ambition - Luke 9:57-58 B. Divine Invitation - Luke 9:59-62. 2. LOVE GOD ABOVE ALL OTHERS A. Sword Of Peace - Matthew 10:34-36 B. Ultimate Love - Matthew 10:37-39. 3. DENY YOURSELF AND FOLLOW CHRIST A. Opposing Views - Matthew 16:21-23 B. Word Or Soul - Matthew 16:24-27. LESSON NUGGETS 1. BE WHOLLY DEVOTED TO CHRIST Luke 9:58-62 ‚úÖÔ∏è From here we can see three people approach Jesus to be His disciples. The first person says, "I will follow you wherever you go." But Jesus replied, "Foxes have dens to live in, and birds have nests, but I, the Son of Man, have no home of my own, not even a place to lay my head." Jesus made this man to know what is involved in following Him. As believers, following Jesus is not just simply saying that you want to follow. It requires commitment and sacrifice. We must stop deceiving people with the idea that there is no commitment or sacrifice required to follow Jesus. Jesus warned this man that following Him is not easy. Following Jesus to wherever He goes is the best path for our life but it is not comfortable or convenient. Our comfort does not come before following Jesus. ‚úÖÔ∏è Jesus said to the second person, "Follow me." The man answered Jesus, "Lord, let me first go and bury my father." The third person said to Jesus, "Lord, I will follow You, but let me first go and bid them farewell who are at my house." Jesus replied him, "No one, having put his hand to the plow, and looking back, is fit for the kingdom of God." Jesus' response to His would-be followers shows that even the most basic "needs" must be sacrificed in order to follow Him. Being a Jesus-follower demands whole-heartedness and the willingness to sacrifice. This aspect of the lesson call each of us to examine our hearts and discern whether we have Jesus' values in view when we promise our devotion and service to Him. Jesus shows us that God wants all people to respond to His invitation ie to follow Him without looking back. 2. LOVE GOD ABOVE ALL OTHERS Matthew 10:34-39 ‚úÖÔ∏è The concept of conflict is evident throughout the Scripture, from prophecy in Genesis that the woman's seed would bruise the head of the Serpent (Genesis 3:15) until Revelation's description of the final defeat of evil (Revelation 20:7-15). Enduring peace will not be a reality until the new heavens and the new earth (Revelation 21:1 through 22:6). When Jesus says that He did not come to bring peace, but a sword, what He is saying is that a complete surrender of our lives to Him will oftentimes put us squarely in conflict with others--even those closest to us. We can see this clearly in the life of someone who might have repented in a family that has rejected Christ. In this instance, the believer's life must be in conflict with his or her family members. Many today have accepted their family decision over God's call. For one to be called a follower of Christ, he or she must be rooted in Him above all else. As believers, our love for Him must be above any kind of love we can have for any of our family members. ‚úÖÔ∏è There are countless stories of how faith in Christ often puts a person in a tense and precarious situation with family and friends. The humble turning to Christ of an individual often stirs the ire and anger of those closest to us that are not believers in Christ themselves. Though most of us may not experience rejection from family or friends, there is a definitive shift that often happens in relationships when a person makes a decision to make Jesus the most important person in their life. There is no middle road to following Jesus. Following Jesus and doing things His way not only makes a Christian a peculiar sort of person, but also makes them an object of ridicule and rejection. DON'T MARRY ANYONE WHO ASK FOR A BREAK IN A RELATIONSHIP Written by Counselor Adolofi Often at times you hear one partner telling the other to give them a break or space or distance because they are not happy with them. People set rules such as 'don't come to my house', 'don't call me', etc. What will happen when the tongue asks for a break from the teeth because of a bite? Only children act like that. Relationship is for the matured man and woman and not boys and girls. There is nothing like a break or space or distance in relationship, in fact it is one of the most difficult but intriguing jobs on earth. A work that has no vacation or mid-terms. Even when you are mad at your spouse, you are expected to value your union over the conflict. You are expected to get back home to your family after work, perform your duties, continue to love and respect your spouse. It is normal for you to stay quiet when the one you love hurts you. It simply means if your love wasn't enough, your words might not matter but that doesn't mean you should go on a break. You never leave them. Your stay means, we may fight but I am not ready to sacrifice the union we have. Many are those who are quick to ask for a break, so they can embark on a search for part-time lovers; and when they don't get what they want, they return to you. But when they succeed, they either ignore you, care less about you or lead you on. Such people are not those you can plan your future with. As far as there is sunshine, there is rain; plants need both to grow. For any relationship to grow stronger, conflict is necessary; it points out your differences, what you need to learn and what you need to work on to be able to become one. Those who run away from conflicts are the very people who are not ready to learn or work on themselves in order to be one with you. Planning your future with such a person is so dangerous, they will leave you in the middle of the road, they will fail you at the time you need them most, they will abandon you at the moment you need a friend to hold on. As human as we are, as wicked we are, as sinful as our nature is, our God does not leave us. The bible says in Hebrews 13:5 (NIV) ‚ÄúNever will I leave you; never will I forsake you". All because of His love for us. It is therefore an error for one to neglect the spouse, or let them be alone because of issues they are confronted with. You are not soft or a fool if you decide to stay, it only means you have a beautiful heart. You know what your partner did to hurt you yet you forgive and stay with them. Your partner grows to love you and he or she is safe with you. To know someone truly loves you, it is in bad times and not in good times; a small fight or misunderstanding can show you how much your spouse feels about you. If you care to know, spouses check their phones for the calls of their partners more frequently when they have misunderstandings than the days when things are going well for them in the relationship. Singles ought to know, marriage is not cheap, it's not easy; it's expensive, it's hard work, it's facing challenges and overcoming them; it's not about looking for an easy route to escape. Marriage has no windows. If he or she is asking for a break, then you better quit the relationship before it leads to . In conclusion "Stop being mean, bad-tempered, and angry. Quarreling, harsh words, and dislike of others should have no place in your lives. Instead, be kind to each other, tender-hearted, forgiving one another, just as God has forgiven you because you belong to Christ" - Ephesians 4:31-32 (TLB). Please share with your friends, someone out there needs this. #GodAmbassador #KK #UncommonMe

So thankful to be here. ‚ù§Ô∏è‚úùÔ∏è God has done an incredible work in our marriage. We are two years married in November and have endured extreme crisis, conflict and fighting for two solid years as well as bankruptcy, multiple health crises and surgeries, having to sell our home and move into an RV, the loss of my seven figure business (I was a New Age coach and not a believer when we met and God finally burned that business down and brought me back to Him. Praise Him!!!üôèüèª) and satanic attacks that included a 6-hour demonic posession that nearly killed me (before I was saved). 28 days after we married my husband broke his neck and was out of work for 18 months. 5 months later he was told he was dying. As his ninth traumatic brain injury, the psychological damage was enormous. He became paranoid, delusional, and suicidally depressed. At his lowest point he stayed in bed for an entire month. If we went 48 hours without a WWIII blowout it was a rarity. I can‚Äôt count the number of times we got ‚Äúthis close‚Äù to divorce, to the point where he went to the courthouse and got all the necessary papers. My husband suffered severe PTSD from an extremely traumatic childhood of every kind of horrific abuse. He is also an ex meth addict and six time ex felon (now believer, clean and sober and making an honest living). And I came into the relationship as a power hungry alpha female and single mom used to running the show. And a hard core New Ager deep in a darkness I had absolutely no idea about. And we both have been diagnosed as bipolar. In every possible way it was a recipe for disaster. üòÜ And disaster it was. For two solid years. And then I came to Christ earlier this year ‚Äî coming back home to my roots as a Christian and my family heritage of priests, pastors and missionaries ‚Äî and Satan ramped it up even more and battled against our marriage relentlessly. I poured myself into walking in God‚Äôs will and learning how to be a godly wife. No matter what I felt my husband was doing (and totally blind to what *I* was doing, of course üòâ). To respecting and honoring him at all times. To submitting to him even when I felt his leadership was so lacking. And to bringing him a gentle and quiet spirit no matter how much I felt justified in my anger, hurt, frustration, and disappointment. After months of surrender to God and submission to my husband and putting these things into practice even though on the outside nothing was changing, suddenly one day while I was driving, I felt an unmistakable shift in my marriage. And I knew it was God placing his hand of grace on us and in that moment I thought, ‚Äúthings are different. They‚Äôre going to be different now.‚Äù And they have been. For three months not a single upheaval. What would have been landmine after landmine was simply a slight ripple on otherwise calm, peaceful, harmonious waters. I kept thinking to myself ‚Äúit‚Äôs like we suddenly received a PhD in emotional intelligence and healthy communication, what happened??!‚Äù God‚Äôs grace happened, that‚Äôs what. In the past two months my husband has had major back surgery, then an emergency appendectomy, then was just recently diagnosed with shingles. On top of his 3x/week migraines. And we have weathered every one with peace and calm. He is wonderful, gentle, loving, strong, adoring, calm, forgiving. And I am learning softness, timing, grace, respect and patience. It is a MIRACLE, in every sense of the word. So. For those struggling, feeling hopeless, feeling like they just can‚Äôt take another minute of the suffering, I hope my story has brought you some hope. God‚Äôs almighty power and grace is SO amazing. ‚ù§Ô∏èüôèüèª‚úùÔ∏è

Building a revolutionary culture is so much more than militancy. Important as that is, I'm skeptical of building anything with someone who's way too into guns and gear as the center of their revolutionary imagery. Militancy should come from a sober assessment of necessity, not macho posturing or a love of violence; as Castro said ‚ÄúRevolutionaries didn't choose armed struggle as the best path, it's the path the oppressors imposed on the people. And so the people only have two choice: to suffer, or to fight." If we're looking to build a better world based on equity and care, there are so many more things we can work on together. Not just these material necessities but also social ones, to handle conflict resolution, restorative justice, and passing on knowledge and values in people-centered ways.

Israel. ‚ù§Ô∏è üáÆüá± As a believer in Jesus, my life has been forever marked by decades of biblical study and visits to the land. The history, archeology, people, culture, food, politics and relationships have changed me. My heart aches for this land. I am not not blinded in dogmatic certainty that this modern state can do no wrong. But there is no moral equivalence between the Jewish state, her right to exist in the land promised by God 3500 years ago, and the current evil assaults to her people and sovereign national interests by an apocalyptic messianic death cult funded by Iran. We cannot understand the modern conflict without understanding the historic spiritual causes. This is NOT a fight over boundaries and Palestinian resistance to an ‚Äúoccupying force‚Äù. Israel‚Äôs History does not start in 1948. She has been given this land and called by God to be a blessing to the whole earth. And we will live to see this truth come to pass. At this moment God has prepared a table for her in the presence of her enemies (Psalm 23) and she will pass through this valley of the shadow of death fearing no evil. For His rod and staff - His strength and authority - comforts her. We agree that goodness and mercy will follower her all the days of her life. And she will dwell securely in the house of the Lord, forever. Remember, God protects His people and His Word does not return to Him void. And if you seek the destruction of the Jewish people you are fighting the Almighty. I fervently pray for Peace in the City of Peace. And there is no peace for one unless there is peace for all. The Arab people are precious to God as well. And millions of them are perpetually being used as fodder in the cannons AntiSemitic hatered spweded by international ‚Äúgovernments‚Äù and state sponsored terrorism. I for one reject the false divide foisted upon us. I am not for Israel and against Palestine. But we should be crystal clear that Hamas, Hezbollah and the Iranian Ayatollahs lurching the world towards total war in the hopes they can entice their Mahadi out of hiding are nothing short of demonic. They seek the total destruction of the Israeli state and the Jewish people. This cannot stand. If you are a believer in Jesus, it‚Äôs time to use your spiritual weapons of war that are mighty in God for the tearing down of strongholds that build themselves up against against the knowledge of God. Prayer is not well wishing. It is the active rejection of darkness that joins the mission of Jesus to destroy the works of the devil. #Israel #prayers #peace #justice

Addo-Carr, Gould set to meet over star‚Äôs Bulldogs future after controversial fortnight Fox League from Fox Sports Bulldogs superstar Josh Addo-Carr has reportedly been summoned to a meeting with general manager of football Phil Gould amid reports his playing future at the club is in doubt. That is according to The Sydney Morning Herald who reports the pair will meet on Friday to discuss their differences. The Herald reports the Bulldogs are frustrated with Addo-Carr after he was involved in two controversies in the last fortnight, while the representative winger feels the club hasn‚Äôt supported him enough through the incidents. Addo-Carr received a two-match suspension last ween for his involvement in a brawl at the Koori Knockout, costing him a Kangaroos jersey. However the 28-year-old is reportedly appealing the sanction. Then this week he shared a controversial post on social media, which he later apologised for. Addo-Carr compared the Middle East conflict to Indigenous land rights. Addo-Carr had posted a photo of Aboriginal and Palestinian flags next to each other with the caption ‚ÄúOne struggle, one fight‚Äù while the phrase ‚ÄúLand Back‚Äù was accompanied by two Arabic words. But via a statement, Addo-Carr later said the post was ‚Äúa mistake‚Äù. He apologised for ‚Äúany offence‚Äù he caused and said he ‚Äúfelt remorse‚Äù as soon as it was brought to his attention that he had got it wrong. Before the two controversies Addo-Carr‚Äôs future at the Bulldogs was reportedly already clouded. He is the club‚Äôs biggest name and arguably best player, who is contracted until the end of 2025. However reports claim that the club expects more from him as a senior player. Addo-Carr joined the Bulldogs in 2022 after five seasons ‚Äî and two premierships ‚Äî with the Storm. He had a disappointing first season in his new colours and as a result lost his spot in the New South Wales Origin side. But a statement month of performances for the Kangaroos in last year‚Äôs Rugby League World Cup ‚Äî and six tries in his first seven games this year ‚Äî helped him earn a recall. He was picked in the Kangaroos squad for the upcoming Pacific Championships but his suspension forced coach Mal Meninga to drop him from the side and bring in Penrith‚Äôs Dylan Edwards. On this day in U.S. Army SF history......12 Oct 1966 ‚Äì 46th Special Forces Company activated Thailand. One of the more exotic assignments for Special Forces Soldiers during the Vietnam War was 46th Company in Thailand. This small unit conducted a variety of missions during the conflict in Indochina. 46th Company was deployed to assist the Thai military in resisting Communist guerrilla activity along the Laotian border, among the hill tribes in the north, and in the south on the Malay Peninsula. Origins of 46th Company. The company was originally organized from personnel of 7th SFGA and reactivated as Company D (Augmented), 1st Special Forces Group (Airborne) in April 1966 at Fort Bragg, North Carolina. Between the activation and deployment, the company underwent pre-mission training. In October of 1966, the unit deployed to Thailand, where an SFOB was established at Camp Pawai, Lopburi, Thailand. On April 15, 1967, the unit was redesignated 46th Special Forces Company (Airborne), 1st Special Forces. Basing. In 1968 the company was headquartered southeast of Lopburi at Camp Pawai. In 1971 the company relocated to the Royal Thai Army (RTA) Special Warfare Center at Fort Narai, Lopburi. (There are different dates mentioned for this relocation; one suggests the move was in December 1967). Mission. The 46th Company conducted specialized Special Forces training at the Royal Thai Army (RTA) Special Warfare Center. Many different Thai military and police units were trained by the 46th. Some of the units trained were the Thai Special Forces cadre and the Border Patrol Police. In addition, in the early 1970s, the 46th trained units of the Cambodian military to include FANK Special Forces units. The Thai Ranger School was founded by 46th Company. Deactivation. The unit departed Thailand in April 1974 and became part of the 1st Special Forces Group at Fort Lewis, Washington. Other sources say the company was deactivated on March 31, 1972. Still another source says the company was deactivated on April 1, 1970, and it was reactivated as United States Army Special Forces, Thailand. ---Mud

üì∑: Brazilian citizens fleeing the conflict between Israel and Hamas arrive at the Galeao Air Force Base in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, on October 11, 2023. Thousands of foreigners find themselves stuck in Israel and across the Palestinian territories, where a full-blown war has erupted since Hamas militants launched their onslaught on Saturday. With the violence having already claimed thousands of lives on both sides, several countries have launched operations to repatriate their citizens, while others plan to do so in the coming days.

Simply dismissing Hamas as a terrorist organization like the U.S and the West have done is a rather unbalanced and too-simplistic way of looking at the Middle East conflict. To be clear, the activities of Hamas meet all the definitions of terrorism. And their reckless and thought-less acts of violence against the Israelis even before legitimately gaining control of Gaza in the 2006 election, are almost always the immediate trigger for the perennial bombardment of that territory with its attendant human and material losses. But, Truth be told, keeping the Palestinians in a state of statelessness for over 7 decades is in itself, an act of war. THIS IS THE BIG ELEPHANT IN THE ROOM. No person with a working conscience should support this. And the unbridled arrogance of the Isrealis which has seen them build settlements in the disputed territory even while negotiation was still going on, is PARTLY responsible for the stunted progress the peace process has witnessed for decades. To be fair, the Palestinians themselves have not helped matters. Their leaders have rejected the two state solution before now. And Hamas violence is PARTLY responsible for what the region has become. You cannot have a group - Hamas - which has the Total Destruction of Israel as its raison d'etre (primary reason for its existence) and this same group enjoys overwhelming support from Palestinians (they won a landslide victory in 2006 Gaza Election, putting them in charge of the territory) and you wonder why the Jewish state is imposing extreme security measures around Gaza??? Is the Israelis supposed to fold their arms and watch Hamas achieve their aim of destroying them? How difficult can it be for Hamas to see that its extreme and I dare say, acts of terror against the Jewish Nation provides a near-perfect justification for any action taken by the Israelis against the over 2 million residents of Gaza. Apparently, destroying Israel is more important than improving the lives of their people within the territory they control. As I type, Israel has cut off food, water and electricity from Gaza. Their hospitals have become one hell of a grave-yard. Their major infrastructure has been destroyed by Israeli bombs. So what exactly has Hamas gained by provoking this current cycle of violence? To make matters worse, the moderate Palestinian group, FATAH which recognises Israel is seen by most Palestinians as SABOTEURS who have been compromised. The only sure way of resolving the situation would have been through A TWO STATE SOLUTION but the practical man in me does not see this happening in the foreseeable future going by the extreme and impossible positions held by both parties in the conflict coupled with the fact that almost all the so-called mediators have continued to allow their own prejudices and biases cloud their sense of fairness.

Response to Middle East conflict The Winnipeg Police Service has been in regular communication with community leaders about the impacts of the war in the Middle East and the fear and insecurity it is creating in Winnipeg. The Service continuously monitors world and local events. It assesses their potential impact on the safety and security of our community and is working closely with leaders to remain abreast of issues and concerns. In response to the terror attack in Israel last weekend, the Service immediately increased patrols around cultural centres, schools, synagogues, mosques and other places of worship across the city. People can expect to see a continued, increased police presence in affected communities. As Chief Danny Smyth said yesterday on behalf of the Canadian Association of Chiefs of Police, ‚ÄúNothing can justify the slaughter of innocent people going about their lives. We are disgusted that anyone would celebrate these attacks, or in any way associate these acts as support for the Palestinian people.‚Äù The Service will continue to deploy resources at rallies and protests to provide a safe and secure environment for the residents of Winnipeg.

„ÄêENG DUB„ÄëKarmic Cause, Karmic Effect, and Hao Liao Ge | Why are Christians less and less free? #god Although humans have free will, they don't understand the truth and reality of the universe and life. Thus, their free will tends to act ignorantly, which is blind action. The inertia energy generated from the actions of free will is called "karma". When free will is constantly acting, karma is accumulated and karmic habits are formed. When karmic habits act back upon free will, it is also known as inertial force, or simply karmic force. We know that while free will is acting, it is influenced by karma. We refer to the function of karma as karmic cause, and the effect of joint actions of free will and karmic cause, as karmic effect. Karmic effects then become new karmic causes, continuing to participate in free will's actions and giving rising to new karmic effects. Operations on the ground have started to open an Academy School for vulnerable and displaced children in Aden, on the same model as Still I Rise Schools in DRC and North-West Syria. Why Yemen? In Yemen, the education crisis is dire. Approximately 2.7 million children lack access to education, facing violence, abuse, child labor, and recruitment into armed groups. Since 2014, Yemen has experienced a conflict between Houthi rebels and the internationally recognized government. Amidst this turmoil, vital infrastructure, like schools and hospitals, were destroyed. Geopolitical rivalries and proxy interests have further inflamed the situation. The number of people who died due to the conflict is estimated to be 377,000, with over half of these fatalities occurring indirectly due to factors like famine and restricted healthcare access. By the year 2022, a staggering count of 16.2 million individuals‚Äîsurpassing half of the entire population‚Äîwere grappling with acute food scarcity. Alongside this, approximately 4.3 million Yemenis have been forced to relocate within the country's borders due to the ongoing crisis. The country's economy is in ruins, with homes, farms, and crucial civilian infrastructure destroyed. The flow of food, heavily reliant on imports, is severely disrupted by the warring factions. Prices are soaring, and many of the poorest have lost their income. The current humanitarian crisis in Yemen has increased the vulnerability of children and women to exploitation, violence and abuse, child labour, killing and maiming, recruitment and use of children by parties to the conflict as combatants. In addition to this, conflict and economic deterioration have compromised people‚Äôs access to health facilities. More than 80% of Yemen‚Äôs population struggles to have safe drinking water and adequate health services. After more than 9 years, Yemen remains one of the the world‚Äôs worst humanitarian crises. EIGHT (8) FORMER REBELS RETURN TO THE FOLDS OF LAW Camp Olivas, City of San Fernando, Pampanga - In a momentous step toward enduring peace and reconciliation, eight (8) former rebels, who had been embroiled in armed conflict with the government, have voluntarily surrendered. This surrender represents a turning point in the continuous efforts to put an end to the prolonged conflict that has afflicted the region for years. These former insurgents chose to lay down their arms and turn themselves over to authorities in Bataan, Olongapo, Tarlac, and Pampanga. Notably, among them were former members of the Communist Terrorist Group (CTG) associated with Anakpawis Bulacan Chapter, Gabriela, Bagong Hukbong Bayan and UGMO (Underground Mass Organization). This event serves as a testament to the effectiveness of the government's reconciliation programs, which have been in place for years. These programs have been dedicated to offering former combatants alternative opportunities for a brighter future and a successful reintegration into society. The government has firmly committed to supporting the rehabilitation and reintegration of these former rebels into society, ensuring they have access to education, job training, and various essential services. PRO3 Regional Director PBGEN JOSE S HIDALGO JR said that while the path to lasting peace is a work in progress, there is no doubt that the decision of these former rebels to withdraw their support from their previous groups is a significant milestone in the ongoing journey toward stability and prosperity for the people. #SerbisyongNagkakaisa #ToServeandProtect #PRO3PartnerNgPamayanan

Edfu temple The Temple of Edfu is an Egyptian temple located on the west bank of the Nile in Edfu, Upper Egypt. The city was known in the Hellenistic period in Koinƒì Greek: ·ºàœÄœåŒªŒªœâŒΩŒøœÇ œÄœåŒªŒπœÇ and in Latin as Apollonopolis Magna, after the chief god Horus, who was identified as Apollo under the interpretatio graeca. It is one of the best preserved shrines in Egypt. The temple was built in the Ptolemaic Kingdom between 237 and 57 BC. The inscriptions on its walls provide important information on language, myth and religion during the Hellenistic period in Egypt. In particular, the Temple's inscribed building texts "provide details [both] of its construction, and also preserve information about the mythical interpretation of this and all other temples as the Island of Creation." There are also "important scenes and inscriptions of the Sacred Drama which related the age-old conflict between Horus and Seth." They are translated by the Edfu-Project.

MAAN Workers Association stands with the Israeli protest movement: ‚Ä¢ for ousting Hamas in Gaza ‚Ä¢ for replacing the Netanyahu government with a democratic regime. On Saturday, October 7th, a crime against humanity was committed in southern Israel. Armed members of Hamas invaded homes and massacred families. At the International Nature and Peace Festival in Re‚Äôim Forest, they killed hundreds. In all, more than a thousand civilians were murdered in cold blood. Thousands more were injured. Over a hundred, including infants, children, women, disabled, and elderly were dragged into Gaza as hostages. Women were raped. Women were also displayed in the streets of Gaza and on media platforms. These horrific acts were not committed by people whose rationality had been warped by the prolonged Israeli siege on Gaza. It was a well-planned and well-organized deed perpetrated by more than a thousand armed men, loyal to a terrorist organization funded by Qatar and the Iranian Ayatollah regime. Hamas took control of Gaza in 2007 in a violent coup against the Palestinian Authority (PA). Since then, it has established its rule over that devastated strip of land, holding Gazans hostage to its fundamentalist ambitions. Ironically, Israel under Netanyahu sought to strengthen Hamas, reasoning that it would weaken the PA and reduce pressure on Israel to negotiate peace. In January 2023, Netanyahu's sixth government was formed, with key positions granted to extreme and fascist elements. Since its establishment, it has worked towards one goal: to eliminate the independence of the judicial system, removing this obstacle to annexing the West Bank. In parallel, the government negotiated economic steps with Hamas, thus recognizing it as the legitimate ruler of Gaza. Against Netanyahu‚Äôs attempt to turn Israel into a dictatorial and halakhic state, an unprecedented protest movement has emerged, involving hundreds of thousands. This movement, which has raised the banner of democracy for all, opposes the settler-controlled apartheid regime in the West Bank. The conflict between the protest movement and the Netanyahu government reached its peak when thousands of reservists, pilots, and senior officers declared that they would refuse to serve in the army if Israel became a dictatorship. The massacre carried out on October 7 in the southern communities of Israel exposed Hamas for what it is: not a liberation movement, not freedom fighters, but an organization of fanatics, twin to ISIS, spreading death and chaos. Simultaneously, the failures of the Netanyahu government were exposed in all their breadth. His full-scale rightwing coalition talked big about security but abandoned its citizens in the hour of need, having shifted most of the army to the West Bank to protect settlers. MAAN Workers Association joins US President Joe Biden and the democratic camp worldwide in calling for the elimination of the Hamas regime in Gaza and the threat it poses to Israelis and Palestinians. After this task is accomplished, we will continue to work with hundreds of thousands of Israelis who have sworn to remove Netanyahu and his extremist partners from the Israeli political scene. We and the rest of the protest movement will strive to build a new democratic alternative in Israel, one that will provide hope for both Israelis and Palestinians, promoting sanity and peace. As an organization that includes in its ranks both Israelis and Palestinians, MAAN opposes the voices that lump all Palestinians with Hamas and call for the flattening of Gaza. It is essential to distinguish between Hamas and the Palestinian people who have been suffocating under Israeli occupation. The just war against Hamas must be conducted while upholding international law, which prohibits harm to civilians. The order of the day is to fight simultaneously against both Hamas and the Netanyahu-Smotrich-Ben Gvir alliance. It is a battle against religious extremism on both sides, in which the fanaticism of one fuels that of the other. Neither represents its people, who in each case yearn for peace and security.

text: Pagi tadi saya telah menjawab soalan daripada YB Tuan Tan Hong Pin dari Parlimen Bakri dalam Sesi Pertanyaan Menteri (MQT) berkenaan langkah-langkah yang diambil Kerajaan Malaysia dalam membantu mangsa di Gaza. Kerajaan Malaysia senantiasa menyalurkan bantuan kepada rakyat Palestin dalam apa jua bentuk dan keadaan. Mengambil kira situasi kritikal pada masa ini, Malaysia menggesa masyarakat antarabangsa termasuk Pertubuhan-Pertubuhan Antarabangsa perlu segera menyalurkan bantuan kemanusiaan seperti bekalan-bekalan asas dan perubatan. Kita juga dalam usaha untuk melakukan evakuasi 5 rakyat Malaysia keluar dari kawasan konflik. Kerjasama antara negara juga sedang giat dijalankan. Bagi pihak Kementerian Luar Negeri, kita telah mengambil inisiatif menubuhkan Tabung Akaun Amanah Kemanusiaan Rakyat Palestin (AAKRP) sejak beberapa tahun dahulu. Sebagai permulaan, saya juga telah menyampaikan bantuan awal RM 1 juta daripada AAKRP untuk diberi kepada rakyat Palestin. Atas sebab itu juga, saya dan beberapa Ahli Parlimen daripada semua pihak tidak kira latar belakang politik telah menyampaikan bantuan ini terus kepada TYT Walid Abu Ali, Duta Besar Palestin ke Malaysia di perkarangan Lobi Parlimen tengah hari tadi. Ini merupakan komitmen berterusan Malaysia dalam membantu rakyat Palestin dalam apa jua cara dan kaedah. AAKRP juga boleh digunakan oleh orang awam atau mana-mana pihak untuk menyalurkan bantuan bagi meringankan beban rakyat Palestin yang terjejas akibat konflik. Sokongan rakyat Malaysia tanpa mengira latar belakang dan pahaman politik menjadi tunjang kekuatan untuk memberi kekuatan kepada rakyat Palestin bagi terus kekal berjuang dan juga sebagai tanda solidariti Malaysia untuk Palestin. ---------------------- Earlier this morning I answered a question posed by YB Tuan Tan Hong Pin (Bakri) in the Minister's Question Session (MQT) regarding measures taken by the Malaysian Government to assist victims in Gaza. The Malaysian government always lend assistance to the Palestinian in any forms. Considering the critical situation at the moment, Malaysia urges the international community including International Organisations to immediately channel humanitarian aids, including basic supplies and medicine. We are also trying to evacuate 5 Malaysians out of the conflict area. Cooperation between countries is also actively being carried out. On behalf of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, we have taken the initiative to establish the Palestine Humanitarian Trust Account Fund (AAKRP) several years ago. For a start, I have delivered an initial aid of RM 1 million from AAKRP to the Palestinian. For that reason too, together with a number of MPs across political divides, we have delivered the aid directly to HE Walid Abu Ali, the Palestinian Ambassador to Malaysia at the Parliament Lobby compound this afternoon. This serves as an indication of Malaysia's continued commitment in assisting the Palestinian. AAKRP can also be used by the public or any party to channel aid to ease the burden of the Palestinian affected by the conflict. The support of Malaysian regardless of background and political divides is a pillar of strength in advancing the Palestinian cause and a sign of Malaysia's solidarity to the Palestine. #wismaputra #doczam #MalaysiaMadani #prayforpalestine
