Does Victorian Socialists support attacks on civilians? Of course not. We're horrified at the many civilian deaths in this conflict. We're socialists (it's in the name). Our politics centres on the collective organisation and resistance of workers, and of ordinary people fighting for a better, fairer and more sustainable world. Will we join in the global chorus of people who think the most important thing right now is to condemn atrocities committed by one specific faction in this decades-long conflict? Also no. It should be clear by now the extent to which such condemnations, however well intended, help Israel justify the massacre it is carrying out in Gaza today (and, retrospectively, all the brutal policies of occupation and apartheid it has imposed on the Palestinians for decades). Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has himself made this clear. In 2019 he told a meeting of his faction in the Israeli Knesset that ‚ÄúAnyone who wants to thwart the establishment of a Palestinian state has to support bolstering Hamas and transferring money to Hamas". This isn't, like much of what has passed for 'facts' about this conflict on social media, 'fake news'. You can read about it in Israeli newspaper Haaretz here: https://archive.md/H8LSL#selection-1147.0-1147.313. The truth is that the quashing of secular, democratic resistance movements among the Palestinians has been a conscious strategy of the Israeli state since its foundation in 1948. You can read about that here: https://redflag.org.au/article/how-israel-strangles-palestines-democratic-resistance. It is worth quoting from the article: "What would a perfect Palestinian resistance look like? Western liberals might like to see forms of activism that respect individual conscience and property rights: petitions, for example, and consumer boycotts. Socialists would no doubt prefer something based on working-class solidarity, strikes and the cross-sectarian mobilisation of the masses. What would Israel do, faced with such morally impeccable and strategically sound opposition? We don‚Äôt have to wonder. Since before the foundation of Israel, Zionists have systematically worked to strangle the development of any such resistance. They have arrested and killed non-violent activist leaders, reshaped the economy of Palestine to disintegrate its workers‚Äô movement, disrupted democratic electoral processes and herded most Palestinians into police states in which normal political organisation is near impossible." As socialists we think our first duty is to stand in solidarity with the Palestinian people in their more than 70 year long struggle for justice. And we think expressing such solidarity should always come first, particularly at a time like now. October 03, 2023 To: Humanitarian organisations Subject: I am not a refugee or a returnee; I am a mother who has lost her children fleeing a conflict Dear world, I have been at the hospital for three weeks, watching over my eight-year-old son and my five-year-old daughter, both suffering from malnutrition. They are not the same as I remember them back in our home city of Khartoum. They are receiving special food and medicines, and a doctor checks their vital signs many times a day. Our lives changed in April. We were a family of eight living in Khartoum. I was at home caring for my six children, and my husband was earning enough as a construction worker. My youngest was a baby who I still breastfed. Needless to say, our home was full, and children were running and playing all over the place. Everything was okay until we heard the bombs and gunshots; neighbours and people we knew were dying. As a family, we decided to leave. My husband stayed behind, and my six children and I embarked on a journey to South Sudan, the country we had originally migrated from. We took a bus, and from one displacement camp to another, we started moving. As we arrived in Alagaya camp within Sudan, the children started to fall sick; they had measles. The baby was the first to get a fever; after one week, the three-year-old and later the nine-year-old one. They died. I had to bury my three children far from home. Far from anyone they knew. Far from where we were going. As I continued my journey to South Sudan, I arrived at Renk, where I discovered that my eight-year-old son and my five-year-old daughter were malnourished. The change in food, the long journey and the grief have been arduous for me and my family. I have lost three children, and the other two are fighting for their lives. Every day at the hospital, I find the strength to look after them. I cook what I can with the other mothers who also have their children at the hospital. We sit under a tree. The other children play; they climb trees, and I can't wait for my children to be among them. Many families here struggle for food and water. Hardly anyone has a proper shelter. As soon as my children feel better, my husband will join us and we will continue our journey, maybe to Malakal. I will try to contact my extended family in South Sudan, but I am uncertain of the future. We would need a lot of courage and help to survive during the coming difficult days to start a new life in South Sudan. My house will still be half full. Your fellow human being, Marta Kaliba Photo: Evani Debone

Larry Schmidt, 89, of Baxter, Iowa, passed away on October 11, 2023. Funeral services for Larry will be held on Saturday, October 14th, 2023, at Baxter High School. Visitation begins at 10:00 A.M. Brunch will be served from 11:00 A.M. to 12:15 P.M. The service will begin at 1:00 P.M. with a graveside committal at Restland Cemetery in Baxter to follow at a later date. Larry was born and raised in Baxter, and he attended Baxter High School. He lived in Baxter the majority of his life and raised his family here in Baxter with his loving wife, Janice. No one could say that Larry wasn't involved in his community. In fact, he made it a point to be as involved as he possibly could. He belonged to Baxter Congregational Church, the Baxter American Legion, was a past member of the Baxter Booster Club, became an EMT for the Baxter Ambulance Crew. Larry held many jobs throughout his life. He was an assembler at Maytag for 31 years, retiring in 1983. You may think retirement would slow him down, but Larry went right on to become a Baxter school bus driver, a position he held for 32 years. He loved spending time with the kids of Baxter over the years. In addition to driving the school bus Monday through Friday, he'd also drive for school trips and would even take bus loads to the Iowa State Fair. He was also a Boy Scout Master and Eagle Scout. Additionally, he had a love of baseball and softball. He was a Fast Pitch Softball pitcher for 40 years, he participated in weekend tournaments, playing in 60-70 games a year and would help coach the kids in his free time. If that wasn't enough, Larry also took pride in working on the Baxter Softball Field. Larry loved his country. He served in the U.S. Army during the Korea Conflict and American Legion. Larry loved life. From fireworks and 4th of July parties, and even being honored as Baxter Grand Parade Marshall twice, he lived loud and proud every single day he could. Whether that was volunteering, driving the school bus, working in his glass repair shop, woodworking, spending time with his grandkids or even just kicking back to enjoy a classic Western or a baseball game, Larry's love for life showed in every part of him. In his later years he enjoyed making wooden trucks and tractors, only to give them away to kids in need. He would say ‚Äúevery kid deserves a toy‚Äù. Larry's memory will be cherished by his wife, Janice (Shore) Schmidt; his sons Gary Schmidt, Ed (Deanna) Schmidt, Brian (Julie) Schmidt, and Adam (Connie) Schmidt; his grandchildren Jason Kutzner, Jamie Schmidt, Marcus (Shelby) Schmidt, Sydney (Chase) Gratopp, Riley Schmidt, Yara, Joseph and River Schmidt; his great-grandchild Asher Schmidt; his sister Joan Smith; his daughter-in-law Sally Schmidt; his many nieces and nephews; and his many, many friends. It was well known that Larry never knew a stranger. Larry was preceded in death by his parents, John and Beulah (Patterson) Schmidt; his son Steven Schmidt; and his siblings Leona Fahrney, Nadine Dee, John Jr. Schmidt, Leland Schmidt, Charles Schmidt, Esther Shattuck, Richard Schmidt, Margaret Ann Swalwell, and Eugene Schmidt. Click the link below to view Larry's obituary and Tribute Wall: https://www.fredregillfunerals.com/obituaries/Larry-Dean-Schmidt?obId=29478705

Gullveig: The goddess and witch of Norse mythology Norse mythology, a rich and complex collection of tales about the gods, heroes, and creatures of ancient Scandinavia, is home to many fascinating characters, some of whom are described in the epic Eddas and other historical texts. One of these characters is Gullveig, a mysterious and powerful woman who is often described as a goddess and a witch. In this article we will look at the myth, meaning and influence of Gullveig in Norse mythology. Origin and narrative The best-known story about Gullveig can be found in the V√∂lusp√°, one of the poems in the Older Edda. The V√∂lusp√° is a prophetic poem sung by a seeress who predicts the creation and end of the world. The poem tells how Gullveig, often associated with gold or with power and wealth, came to the gods and was thrown into the fire three times and reborn each time. Her name itself can be translated as "gold power" or "gold addiction". This act of violence against Gullveig was one of the catalysts for the war between the Aesir and the Vanir, the two main groups of Norse gods. The interpretations of Gullveig Gullveig is an elusive character, and there are various interpretations as to who she really was and what role she played in mythology. Gullveig as a goddess of wealth and power: Some believe that Gullveig was a goddess of wealth and power. Her name, meaning "Gold Power," may indicate her connection to gold and power. She could also be seen as the embodiment of human desires and temptations. Gullveig as a witch and sorceress: Some interpretations portray Gullveig as a powerful witch or sorceress who was able to regenerate through her powers and spells. The fact that she was burned and reborn three times could demonstrate her magical abilities and immortality. Gullveig as a connection between the Aesir and the Vanir: Since the conflict over Gullveig led to the war between the Aesir and the Vanir, she could also be seen as a symbolic figure that embodies the tensions and differences between the two groups of gods. Gullveig's influence and significance The myth of Gullveig has profound meanings in Norse mythology. First, it shows the tensions and conflicts between the different groups of gods and how human emotions such as envy, greed and power can further exacerbate these tensions. Secondly, the story of Gullveig also highlights the power and importance of women in Norse mythology. Despite the violence inflicted on her, Gullveig could not be destroyed. This could be seen as evidence of the strength, resilience and power of women in an often male-dominated world. Finally, Gullveig is also a symbol of eternal regeneration and rebirth. Despite all the adversities she faced, she was continually reborn, suggesting the cyclical nature of life and the eternal cycle of death and rebirth. Closing remarks The story of Gullveig is a captivating and enigmatic piece of Norse mythology. She embodies many of the central themes and motifs of these myths: conflict, power, regeneration and the role of women. Even though many questions about her remain unanswered, the figure of Gullveig offers a fascinating insight into the thoughts and ideas of the ancient Scandinavians. by Jatukham Ramathep

The miserable fact of The Voice: We were always destined to get to this point By Niki Savva and The Sydney Morning Herald When Peter Dutton ran for the Liberal leadership in 2018, he twice asked Ken Wyatt to vote for him. Dutton told Wyatt he wanted him on his frontbench. Wyatt told Dutton both times that he would not vote for him. Furthermore, he told him that if he became leader, he would not serve under him, he would quit the ministry. Beyond expressing concern for the sexual abuse of children, Dutton showed little interest in Indigenous issues, according to Wyatt. When we spoke a few days ago, Wyatt was as unsurprised as he was unimpressed by Dutton‚Äôs conduct of the No campaign in the referendum. Wyatt dismissed the fevered commentary about Jacinta Nampijinpa Price becoming prime minister. He reckons for a leader to succeed, she ‚Äì or he ‚Äì must be capable of, and be seen to be working for, all Australians. He believes neither Dutton nor Price has shown they can do that. Going down in history as two of the people most responsible for destroying a referendum which Wyatt is convinced would help Indigenous people is no qualification for national leadership in Wyatt‚Äôs view. Born on a mission station to a mother who was forced to hand over her wages to bureaucrats then ask for money back to buy essentials, Wyatt was the first Indigenous person to become Indigenous affairs minister under Scott Morrison. He quit the Liberal Party in protest in April. Clinging to hope that Yes would triumph, Wyatt worried defeat would deter future governments from considering new approaches. He accepts Anthony Albanese would have no mandate to legislate a Voice but pledged he and fellow Yes warriors would not give up fighting for better ways to address Indigenous disadvantage. In the post-mortems which will inevitably continue for decades, we can and we will blame No campaigners for playing filthy dirty, for putting politics above everything else, for using loudhailers to whistle up the neo-Nazis, racists and bigots with lies and misrepresentations. The demons unleashed by tactics to foment conflict, for short term political gain at the expense of vulnerable Australians, will live on long after Saturday‚Äôs vote. We can and will blame the Albanese government for choosing the wrong time or the wrong words or for mismanaging the campaign, for doing it now, or even for doing it at all. The miserable fact is that no matter the wording, the content, or the timing, we were always destined to get to this point. A few Yes campaigners, including Wyatt, firmly believe this. There was never going to be bipartisanship. Releasing exposure draft legislation would only have given the Noes more ammunition. Legislating the Voice alone would have once again been whitefellas telling blackfellas what was best for them. Delaying the referendum until the next election would have guaranteed the loss of both the election and the referendum. Yes advocates say the Noes tapped into a deep well of racism, others that the referendum has created a hell of a mess. The Noes blame Yes for dividing Australia, which is a bit like claiming black is white. They claim it‚Äôs the biggest change to the Constitution ever proposed. Wrong. That was the republic. Their most potent argument against that was if it ain‚Äôt broke don‚Äôt fix it. Those same people, notably Tony Abbott, know this system is broken, offer no solution and instead seek to destroy the Voice by claiming it will encourage ‚Äúseparatism.‚Äù As if such a modest change to set up an advisory body creates a new apartheid. Confronted by tough questioning, they scream bias. In fact, they have had a good run. Too good. As the most prominent, the most effective and most polarising participant in the black-on-black conflict, Price has called the shots for the Coalition. She says up front what many of them think but few dare to say. The photo of Price acting as barista in a Perth cafe with Dutton smiling awkwardly behind her like a mobile coffee caddy, says it all. (Image 2) Not only has she has given white folk an excuse to vote no, she has absolved them of any guilt or shame for past wrongs by insisting colonisation had benefited Aboriginal people. Read David Marr‚Äôs excellent book Killing for Country and judge for yourself. Another of the many low points of this campaign was when the media and others perversely condemned Indigenous leader Marcia Langton for calling out racism, rather than condemn the racism itself. We live in dangerous times when Ray Martin cops more abuse from the Noes for using words like dinosaurs and dickheads than does a neo-Nazi who threatens to kill a senator. Dutton questioning the integrity of an institution as highly regarded as the Australian Electoral Commission was inexcusable. It opened the door wide for conspiracy theorists to harass and abuse the commission and its staff. This is a defining moment for Australia. To make sense of the world today it is vital to understand how propaganda works, how insidious it is and just how prevalent it has become. "Probably every conflict is fought on at least two grounds: the battlefield and the minds of the people via propaganda. The good guys and the bad guys can often both be guilty of misleading their people with distortions, exaggerations, subjectivity, inaccuracy and even fabrications, in order to receive support and a sense of legitimacy. "Propaganda can serve to rally people behind a cause, but often at the cost of exaggerating, misrepresenting, or even lying about the issues in order to gain that support ... As the various examples below will show, common tactics in propaganda often used by either side include: ‚Ä¢ Using selective stories that come over as wide-covering and objective. ‚Ä¢ Partial facts, or historical context ‚Ä¢ Reinforcing reasons and motivations to act due to threats on the security of the individual. ‚Ä¢ Narrow sources of experts to provide insights in to the situation. (For example, the mainstream media typically interview retired military personnel for many conflict-related issues, or treat official government sources as fact, rather than just one perspective that needs to be verified and researched). ‚Ä¢ Demonizing the enemy who does not fit the picture of what is right. ‚Ä¢ Using a narrow range of discourse, whereby judgments are often made while the boundary of discourse itself, or the framework within which the opinions are formed, are often not discussed. The narrow focus then helps to serve the interests of the propagandists." [...] "The list of tactics used in propaganda listed further above is also expressed in a similar way by Johann Galtung, a professor of Peace Studies and summarized here by Danny Schechter: "[Professor] Galtung laid out 12 points of concern where journalism often goes wrong when dealing with violence. Each implicitly suggests more explicit remedies. ‚Ä¢ Decontextualizing violence: focusing on the irrational without looking at the reasons for unresolved conflicts and polarization. ‚Ä¢ Dualism: reducing the number of parties in a conflict to two, when often more are involved. Stories that just focus on internal developments often ignore such outside or external forces as foreign governments and transnational companies. ‚Ä¢ Manicheanism: portraying one side as good and demonizing the other as evil. ‚Ä¢ Armageddon: presenting violence as inevitable, omitting alternatives. ‚Ä¢ Focusing on individual acts of violence while avoiding structural causes, like poverty, government neglect and military or police repression. ‚Ä¢ Confusion: focusing only on the conflict arena (i.e., the battlefield or location of violent incidents) but not on the forces and factors that influence the violence. ‚Ä¢ Excluding and omitting the bereaved, thus never explaining why there are acts of revenge and spirals of violence. ‚Ä¢ Failure to explore the causes of escalation and the impact of media coverage itself. ‚Ä¢ Failure to explore the goals of outside interventionists, especially big powers. ‚Ä¢ Failure to explore peace proposals and offer images of peaceful outcomes. ‚Ä¢ Confusing cease-fires and negotiations with actual peace. ‚Ä¢ Omitting reconciliation: conflicts tend to reemerge if attention is not paid to efforts to heal fractured societies. When news about attempts to resolve conflicts are absent, fatalism is reinforced. That can help engender even more violence, when people have no images or information about possible peaceful outcomes and the promise of healing. - Danny Schechter, Covering Violence: How Should Media Handle Conflict?, July 18, 2001" To read more: https://www.globalissues.org/article/157/war-propaganda-and-the-media In the words of the father of modern propaganda, Edward Bernay‚Äôs; ‚ÄúTHE conscious and intelligent manipulation of the organized habits and opinions of the masses is an important element in democratic society. In every conflict, it is children who are the most vulnerable.

With every airstrike, rocket, and bullet fired, children‚Äôs sense of security is ripped away.

For several days now, we have been living in pain, in confusion, in a painful sense of helplessness that makes us fragile, vulnerable, disoriented, and above all, deeply saddened. For there is nothing more contagious than the pain of innocent men, women, old people and children.

 The horror of innocent humans brutally torn from their loved ones, beaten, imprisoned, tortured and diabolically terrorized is something that tears at the heart of anyone with a heart capable of beating for their fellow man.

 As parents, how can we not put ourselves in the shoes of those parents whose children's fate is unknown to them!

 As human beings, how can we not feel the dramatic echo of so much suffering!

 As human beings, where can we find hope, optimism, joy of life, when so much of our unfortunate humanity can go?

Yet each of us knows in his conscience that every conflict, from the most trivial to the most bitter, is always and only an intellectual accident. We all know the weapons with which we could avoid their tragic consequences. What prevents us from using them?

 As people of faith, we pray with all our hearts that this will end as soon as possible; that everyone will be able to reunite with their loved ones and return to their homes. Let us pray. Let us pray with contrite hearts, with consistency and intensity, hoping in our hearts that this will end soon.

I think there's just too much pressure that people put on the word Love.

Like it's just supposed to solve everything. Like it's a cure all to every problem and that just by saying "I love you" everything magically becomes okay.

But then why do so many of us look for someone else to talk to when something goes wrong? Why do we seek out someone who maybe be more willing to listen to what we are going through and give us advice? Why do we want someone who understands what we are going through rather than just someone who tells us they love us?

It's so hard to be one person, now imagine what it's like having to deal with all the emotions of two.

And maybe that's why people are always so unsure about love. Why things go down hill so often when there is a fight. Why they run away from any kind of conflict. And why we seek out the company of old friends who have known us for a while to sit with and talk to.

It's hard to open up to someone and harder still when it's about something that scares you. And I know love scares you. Losing someone you care about scares you.

Which is why sometimes just being understanding of someone's emotions, of their fears, of what they are going through in life is enough.

Friends who share memes are sometimes even more appreciated that one's who share love notes.

Because sometimes, understanding is just better than love.

India is putting in place a major operation to evacuate its citizens who wish to return from conflict-hit Israel. Announcing the initiative late on Wednesday, External Affairs Minister S. Jaishankar said special chartered flights are being arranged. 

This will be the second evacuation this year, after Operation Kaveri that brought back several thousand Indian citizens from conflict-torn Sudan in April-May. 

‚ÄúLaunching Operation Ajay to facilitate the return from Israel of our citizens who wish to return. Special charter flights and other arrangements being put in place. Fully committed to the safety and well-being of our nationals abroad,‚Äù posted Mr. Jaishankar on X, formerly Twitter. 

The Indian Embassy in Tel Aviv stated that it has emailed the first lot of registered Indian citizens for the special flight that is expected to take off for India on Thursday. ‚ÄúMessages to other registered people will follow for subsequent flights,‚Äù said the embassy in a post on X.

The announcement has come days after Air India suspended its service in the Delhi-Tel Aviv route as Hamas carried out a crippling attack on Israel last Saturday. Following that ground, sky and sea attack, Israel has launched a massive military strike against Gaza Strip. The rapid escalation has also drawn the Hezbollah in southern Lebanon, which has lobbed rockets at Israel‚Äôs northern territory drawing Israeli strikes. The situation has turned the sky above Israel risky prompting cancellation of many international flights. 

A source indicated that the scale of Operation Ajay will depend on demand and that the government will augment capacities depending on further need.

Control room set up
India has been preparing for the escalating situation soon after the conflict erupted on Saturday. On Wednesday, the Ministry of External Affairs set up a 24-hour control room, which will operate simultaneously from New Delhi, Tel Aviv and Ramallah in the Palestinian territory.

World News:
Amid the escalating Israel-Hamas conflict, the European Union has called on the CEOs of Meta and X to take proactive measures against "misinformation" on its platforms. 

In a recent letter, Thierry Breton, the EU's commissioner for Internal Market, expressed concerns to Meta CEO Mark Zuckerberg regarding the "surge of illegal content and disinformation being disseminated in the EU via certain platforms." Breton emphasized the need for Meta to uphold the Digital Services Act's mandates, noting that platforms should exhibit "timely, diligent and objective action" against flagged illegal content and enforce "proportionate and effective mitigation measures."

X, previously known as Twitter, received a similar warning from Breton. He said that despite warnings, questionable content persisted on X's platform, underscoring the responsibility of owner Elon Musk to intervene when necessary. Breton advised Musk to be "very transparent and clear" regarding permissible content and to consistently apply and bolster platform policies, especially considering potential threats to public security and accurate discourse.

Responding to these critiques, X's trust and safety team asserted their commitment to ensuring platform integrity. They announced the removal of specific Hamas-linked accounts and the deletion of "tens of thousands of posts" containing "violent or hate-driven content."

STARTING PREP üñçÔ∏è
Walking into school orientation for Lola had me reflecting on all the nerves I had as a first time school mama and so, while I have these fresh in my mind I thought I‚Äôd share ‚úèÔ∏è‚Äô5 Things I Wish I Knew about having a School Kid‚Äô ‚úèÔ∏è 

The last one is what impacted us the most!

‚úèÔ∏è Checking they can open everything independently in their lunch box. Do a practice run and see if there is anything you pack that they struggle to open on their own. 
‚úèÔ∏è Schedule time in the weeks before and the week starting, to implement school life admin into your life. I was SO unaware of just how much school life entails. Man, oh man, the apps?!? If you set aside half an hour a week to keep an eye on these things you shouldn‚Äôt miss too many notices (lol.) 
‚úèÔ∏è If your kid gets homework, consider making time in the morning to do it. We found they have more brain energy and clarity then. Something to consider if afternoons aren‚Äôt working for you.
‚úèÔ∏è Dinner time chats- These have been so important. We don‚Äôt do this EVERY evening but sharing the tough parts about your day can help normalise vulnerability and conflict resolution as a family. Sharing a highlight and a lowlight of your week with them and asking them to do the same starts these conversations early.
‚úèÔ∏è You may find your Preppie overwhelmed and tired - ESPECIALLY towards the end of the their terms. It‚Äôs like they‚Äôre running a marathon and along the way adapting, absorbing so much information socially, emotionally and mentally. As they get to the week 10 mark, you may find they‚Äôre like we are when we‚Äôre tired- emotional, hungry, cranky, short-fused, you get the gist. LOTS of TLC in those weeks, they are doing their absolute best and it‚Äôs taking everything of them.

I hope these help, please feel free to jump into the comments if you have anything you find really helpful üíó

How many times do you feel triggered in your relationship, have an urge to respond habitually in a way that doesn‚Äôt work, recognize the urge and choose to do something new‚Ä¶‚Ä¶but not know what do instead? 
This is a very stuck feeling and definitely adds another layer of anxiety to the situation. 
My intention with this post is to provide you with some new options to work on. As you read through, try to visualize how you might implement these strategies into a familiar conflict between you and your partner. Visualizing can help your brain pathways wire around a new event, even if the new event isn‚Äôt taking place physically. This gives you the opportunity to practice new behaviors and feelings (conjuring up the feeling of empathy, for example) so you‚Äôre better prepared  when tough situations arise.

In 1969, violence broke out in Northern Ireland leading to 30 years of conflict known as the Troubles. Despite the use of the terms Protestant and Catholic to refer to the two sides, the conflict was primarily political rather than religious. Nationalists, who were mostly Irish Catholics, wanted a united Ireland, and loyalists, who were mostly Ulster Protestants, were in favor of Northern Ireland remaining part of the United Kingdom. Sectarian lines still divide parts of Northern Ireland today, 24 years after the 1998 Good Friday Agreement largely ended the Troubles.

Seen here: a youth wears a gas mask during clashes with British troops in Londonderry, Northern Ireland. People had been fleeing from teargas after a night of street fighting.

The attack by Hamas in recent days arrived just as it seemed Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was about to complete his masterpiece: peace with the Arab world while completely ignoring the Palestinians.

The African Tribe reinterpreting Victorian Era garments from the 1900sü™°

Meet the Herero, a people who live mostly in Namibia, Africa

But why would an African tribe wear traditionally Western clothes? If you have some sense of African history, the answer may not come as a great surprise: in short, it has to do with a painful colonial experience:

During the 20th century, Namibia used to be a German colony. Around the year 1900, a severe conflict broke out between the Germans and the Herero.
Women took up foreign dresses, modifying them to appear somewhat like the cattle (an important part of Herero society).
The men claimed the military uniform of the dead bodies of German soldiers.

Today, the military dress is a tribute to these struggles.

During these battles, Herero population was reduced by nearly 80%. 

‚ÄúThe dresses and uniforms are extremely important and powerful symbols of Herero culture, and here is the paradox, as the clothing comes from (or is directly influenced by) the people who nearly wiped them out altogether.‚Äù - Jim Naughten

I still strongly pray for the Jewish lives lost and mourn with my Jewish friends and neighbors as they live through this devastating moment.

I cannot in good conscience sit and vote yes on a resolution that does not ask for a de-escalation of violent retribution launched by Israel against largely civilian territory. 

The Palestinian children also deserve someone to stand up for them and condemn their murder. Those babies who right now are denied water, electricity and medicine, deserve to have someone stand up for them and condemn their abuse. An abuse they have suffered for over 75 years. With over 6,000 Palestinian lives lost since 2008 and thousands more injured and displaced

I stand with the Palestinians who for too long have been ignored, demonized, dehumanized, and refused the dignity and humanity all humans deserve.

I stand with Israelis who have called out the inhumanity of the apartheid state and have called for full rights and safety for all citizens of Israel and Palestine. 

It is time to call for true justice and apply the values of universal human rights to all victims of oppression, regardless of nationality, religion or skin color. 
I send my prayers for peace and the protection of innocent lives lost during this conflict. Be it Israeli, Palestinian, American or any other loss of life. 

Israeli writer Gideon Levy stated:
‚ÄúWe now have to cry bitterly for the Israeli victims, but we should also cry for Gaza"
And finally to quote my favorite verse in the Quran: ‚ÄúO you who believe, be upholders of justice - witnesses for God, even though against yourselves or your parents, and kinsmen.‚Äù 4:135

‚úçÔ∏è @jeremycorbyn ‚ÄúI Condemn Violence Against All Civilians, Why Can‚Äôt Keir Starmer?‚Äù

In an interview with LBC, Keir Starmer was asked whether ‚Äúcutting off power and water‚Äù to 2 million people, half of whom are children, was appropriate. He agreed that Israel ‚Äúhas that right‚Äù. Where is the empathy for Palestinians who have lost their loved ones, their homes and their futures? What happened to the universal application of international law?

We may be witnessing the beginning of the total annihilation of Gaza and its people. This is not a battle between one state and another. It is couched as an Israeli response to a non-state actor, but in fact it is a response to Palestinian people wherever they are. What is unfolding is not a conflict of equals, but the systematic starvation, subjugation and destruction of an unarmed civilian population.

I wonder, if Gaza is wiped off the face of the earth, whether our politicians will look back and reflect on the reality of their unwavering support. This cannot justify the indiscriminate killing of Palestinians, who are paying a price for a crime they did not commit. All human life is equal. Why is it so difficult for our politicians to be consistent in this basic moral principle?

I made the caption from my previous post into a slide series to share. These are practices I‚Äôve outlined in detail in my book Raising Critical Thinkers. Thanks for your thoughtful interest in these ideas. I especially thank you for sharing with others. I wrote my book because I believe critical thinking is the key skill we desperately need today in all our educating and discourse. üôèüèº
‚Äî
[images: Here‚Äôs how I process wildly traumatic and shocking news.

I begin by reading. I do my best to start with ‚Äúnot knowing.‚Äù I know my feelings, but I don‚Äôt know the full story. I give myself permission to not know how to interpret the news even while I read it and watch it. I notice my knee-jerk reaction to the barrage of opinions we hurl at one another‚Äîthe pressure to say the right thing, to avoid the wrong thing. I discover how I lean and I get curious about why. I wonder about how someone I respect sees the same information so differently from another person I respect.

Then I read all the perspectives I can that make me the most uncomfortable. I try to imagine more perspectives than the one I automatically adopt. I add the grief of as many parties as I can hold. I list in my mind the questions I can‚Äôt answer easily. I feel my feelings: revulsed, hopeless, angry, shocked, defeated, frightened.

I don‚Äôt assume I am getting the full story from any one source. I know that reading and media cannot tell me what I haven‚Äôt lived. My perspective will always be one of learner, not expert. South Korea is finding itself in a difficult position as the war between Israel and Palestinian militant group Hamas escalates further. President Yoon Suk Yeol has condemned Hamas' "indiscriminate" attacks, yet he has not openly expressed support for Israel, in what is viewed as a balancing act amid fears that the ongoing war may expand to a wider Middle East conflict.

During a meeting between Yoon and a six-member U.S. bipartisan Senate delegation led by Majority Leader Chuck Schumer during the latter's visit to Seoul, Wednesday, Schumer urged the South Korean government to stand with Washington in supporting Israel. "I urged President Yoon to continue to stand with the Israeli people and do all he can to join the U.S. by supporting Israel‚Äôs effort to defend itself. I described the atrocities committed by Hamas terrorists," Schumer wrote on X, the platform formerly known as Twitter, Thursday. "I saw he was moved and affirmed South Korea‚Äôs commitment to Israel‚Äôs security," he added.

But an official statement released by Yoon's office on the meeting with the U.S. Senate delegation did not mention South Korea's commitment to Israel's security. "The president and the Senate delegation condemned Hamas' indiscriminate attacks on Israel and expressed their empathy for the need for South Korea and the U.S. to play a constructive role in bringing a swift end to the current situation, easing tensions in the region and achieving stability," read the statement released by the presidential office on Wednesday evening.

The somewhat differing tone between the top U.S. senator and the South Korean presidential office suggests that Seoul is trying to maintain a diplomatic balance in the decades-long Israel-Palestine strife, one of the world's most intractable conflicts.

The assault and dastardly attack on dog feeders is deplorable and deeply disturbing. Dog feeders do a wonderful service to society because they help create friendlier dogs who are calm, instead of starving, and who will not bite and are easier to catch for sterilisation and vaccination. 

It is the statutory responsibility of every housing society to designate feeding spots for community animals in consultation with the caregivers/dog feeders, as per the mandate under Rule 20 of the Animal Birth Control (ABC) Rules, 2023. This will also help reduce man animal conflict, cases of dog bites, etc.

Rule 20(2) of the ABC Rules, 2023 clearly states that in case of any conflict between the housing society and the animal caregivers or other residents, an animal welfare committee shall be formed. 

The Bombay High Court, recently, on 24 April 2023 in Vineeta Tandon vs. State of Maharashtra & Ors reiterated that the ABC Rules, 2023 have the force of law & it is not open to any housing society to say it will not abide by the law.

On 4 August, the Germans launched an offensive by using the 6th Army and elements of the 4th Panzer Army. The battle degenerated into¬†house-to-house fighting¬†as both sides poured reinforcements into the city.

Follow @faces_of_ww1

German tactics followed a successful pattern:¬†Luftwaffe airstrikes, then artillery, then advancing infantry with tanks in support. Unfortunately there were never enough artillery, infantry, and tanks to do the job swiftly and although the pattern was effective it still came with a high cost in casualties.

Soviet and Russian tactics specified that¬†tanks would lead the assault in city fighting followed by infantry fighting vehicles and dismounted infantry. Tank columns would move in herringbone formation along city streets.

Stalingrad was the first great extended urban conflict in the history of modern warfare, and¬†functionaries on both sides came to resemble close-quarter hit-and-run guerrillas.

By the end of the Korean War, the F-86 was credited for shooting down 792 MiGs, at the loss of only 78 Sabres. It's important to note that this is not an accurate representation of the MiGs capability compared to the Sabre, as many Sabre pilots were experienced WWII veterans, competing against largely inexperienced Chinese and Korean pilots. During the conflict, 41 pilots achieved Ace status, 40 of which flew the Sabre, the exception being a navy F4U night fighter pilot. It is argued that Sabre‚Äôs only downed around 200 MiGs, after an internal investigation for more accurate numbers. On the opposite side of the conflict, Soviet and Chinese records claim over 800 sabres shot down, which cannot be reconciled by US records. So it‚Äôs impossible to find an accurate number of Sabre VS MiG ratios.¬†

During the conflict, the Soviets managed to capture one single example of an F-86, that had avoided destruction by USAF crew, after it crash landed on a beach, before being submerged. The Soviet‚Äôs were able to recover a US G-suit, and the radar gun sight as well. The gun sight would be reproduced as the ASP-4N gunsight, and would be installed on the MiG-17, that would later be used during the Vietnam War.¬†

The Sabre would be used in numerous conflicts, and in multiple militaries during its service, playing a critical role in aviation history.¬†

MCC‚Äôs work will build on previous responses to the ongoing conflict, including the distribution of food and bedding for those affected. From my book: Ever heard of the Qana massacre ? The UN is saying today  that airstrikes in Gaza are directly hitting its shelters and have damaged five other schools-turned-shelters. Israel claims to be hitting Hamas military targets and locations. This makes me think of our own history in Lebanon. One moment in our collective memoire that has traumatized me as a child and which I briefly mention in the introduction of my book ALL SHE LOST: In 1996, Israel launched its ‚ÄúGrapes of Wrath‚Äù operation on the south of Lebanon , which it was occupying at the time. On April 18, 1996 the IDF shelled a UN shelter near the village of Qana - where at least 800 people were taking refuge. 106 people are killed, half of them are children. Israel claimed that there were close Hezbollah targets to the UN compound - but a UN investigation found that the Israeli attack on the base ‚Äúwas likely not an accident,‚Äù and an Amnesty International investigation concluded that it was intentional. War crimes have been committed by Israel many times in the history of this conflict and with NO accountability. The vicious cycle of violence will only make everyone worse off especially the innocent civilians of Gaza. No one will be safe on the long run if the root cause of the problem- that is occupation and what humanitarian and human rights organizations have called Apartheid - is not resolved.

Israel was founded in 1948. About half of the Jews worldwide migrated to Palestine to create their own state after 2000 years of being in diaspora. They had plans for this going back to the 1880s but the aftermath of WW2 sped up their urgency to relocate. The only problem was that there was already people in Palestine, Jews only bought 6% of the total land, and Jews wanted a Nation to themselves. So they violently kicked out 700,000 natives in an event called the Nakba (Catastrophe) then claimed 78% of the land theirs. There has been 3 major wars since over that event and Israel has held their ground on their newly claimed territory. 

Israel started the conflict between the Palestinians by stealing their homeland and they kill 10x as many people as the Palestinians do. The Hamas invasion was to be expected. I‚Äôm not saying it‚Äôs justifiable but certain actions taken by Israel made the war inevitable. Palestine has been under violent occupation and blockaded for decades. The reason most Americans don‚Äôt hear about it or see the graphic videos is because Jews own/control the Media, Congress, Blackrock, Universities, Facebook, Instagram, Google, YouTube, ADL and many other important institutions in our society which shape the publics consensus.

The non-Jewish supporters of Israel in America I see are mostly empathetic Christians. It‚Äôs understandable why they would post things like ‚ÄúI stand with Israel‚Äù during these times, they don‚Äôt want to see innocent civilians dying. But they don‚Äôt truly understand the full political context of the situation or know that Israel started the conflict and they kill 10x as many Civilians than Palestinians do. Also Jews aren‚Äôt very fond of Christians.

Israel is 30x richer and they have the upper hand on a massive military power imbalance so they aren‚Äôt under any real existential threat. They allowed the limited invasion to happen as a pretext for War. Israels real motive is to annex Palestine and drag us into a war with Iran.

Ask yourself do you want to fight a war in Iran for the benefit of Israel? I don‚Äôt. The American interest is to make sure that never happens. Blindly supporting Israel inches us closer to the possibility.

Re posting my friend @jehane11 ‚Äòs great post: Our most powerful response to the horror in Israel and Palestine is to refuse to surrender our humanity. You will be told by some: The deaths of Israeli children are unfortunate but inevitable, because Israel‚Äôs occupation of Palestine is brutal and wrong. You will be told by others: The deaths of Palestinian children are unfortunate but inevitable, because it is the only way to keep Israel safe from terror, and Hamas brought this on its own people. Both will say: Our aggression is the only response to their aggression, our fear more justified than their fear, our grief more devastating than theirs ever will be. But ‚Ä¶the hierarchy of pain is the old way.The moment we allow our hearts to go numb is the moment we shut down our humanity. I don‚Äôt know the solution to the conflict in Israel and Palestine, but I do know the starting point:To grieve ‚Äútheir‚Äù children as our children. 
It‚Äôs the only way to break the cycle. 
To my loved ones who are Israeli, Jewish,and Palestinian: I see your searing pain. I love you and grieve with you and am reciting my ancestors‚Äô prayers for protection as you search for your families and bear the unbearable.May love find you through the impossible.To all of us witnessing this story: What does love want you to do? 
If you cannot look at the news and the images: It‚Äôs okay. Step away, be with the earth, go to the trees, let them breathe through you; remember that you don‚Äôt need to do all the things, just the one that‚Äôs yours to do. If you want to help but don‚Äôt know how: Begin in relationship. Who in your life is hurting from this? Offer to walk with them, listen to them. There is no fixing grief, only bearing it together. Only then do we know what to do next. 
If you‚Äôre falling apart: Your breathlessness is not a sign of your weakness, but of your strength. Of how deeply you feel the horror, how deeply you care.You still feel. And that matters in a world that wants us to feel nothing. Who can feel it with you? breathe with you? Opening our hearts to grief‚Äîothers and our own‚Äîis how we hold our humanity in a world that would destroy it. It‚Äôs how we will begin to survive this.Poem by @valariekaur

Repairing after an argument is the process of resolving and rebuilding the relationship.  It's a necessary conflict-management tool. And it‚Äôs especially important for our little ones.

Kids *seem* to get over things pretty quickly. Their minds are always looking for the next thing to hold their attention. But, in reality, the way we interact with our kids can stick with them for longer than we‚Äôd like to admit.

So, in the short term, repair helps us to mitigate any immediate emotional and behavioral issues related to us losing our cool. It pushes pause on our anger and makes room for normalcy.

In the long-term, repair has even more important repercussions. 

Repair continues to build trust, confidence, and connection in our relationship with our kids. They learn they can express their feelings and be heard and acknowledged. That leads to healthy attachment, which is a necessary part of healthy development. And modeling these repair skills will also imprint important communication and problem-solving skills onto our kids.

Do you want me to walk you through the repair process in real-time? 

‚ú® Join me and @momwell for a *free* masterclass where we teach you our step-by-step process for repair.  Comment REPAIR below and I‚Äôll send you the info!

What happened:  Filmmaker and philanthropist Jemima Goldsmith recently took to social media to express her stance on the ongoing Israeli-Palestinian conflict. Her comments ignited a debate among followers, both in Pakistan and internationally, as she called for condemning both sides of the conflict while emphasizing the importance of international law and human rights.

Details: Jemima Goldsmith posted on social media, stating, "I stand with the innocent human beings on both sides of this conflict. Condemn both." In another post, she shared a text-based message that read, "I stand with International Law and Human Rights. There is no humanity in political tribalism."

More: Jemima Goldsmith's comments drew many reactions, particularly among Pakistanis. While some expressed support and pride in her stance, others were disappointed. Critics argued that her statements were vague and suggested that she take a clearer position. Some compared her view to "all lives matter," meaning it did not effectively address the specific issues. The debate also touched on colonization and its implications for human rights and international law.

The Green Party of Canada unequivocally condemns all violence taking place in Palestine and Israel. We are deeply concerned about the well-being of the hostages kidnapped and threatened by Hamas and the ongoing, unlawful Israeli siege on Gaza.

 Last weekend, Hamas conducted horrendous attacks that have shocked and continue to shock the conscience of humanity, brutally targeting civilians and taking many hostages. We condemn these violations of international law unequivocally.

We call on the Canadian government to do all in our power to de-escalate the conflict and to ensure the safety of the hostages and secure their immediate release. The safety of the hostages is a clear priority.

In response to last weekend‚Äôs attacks by Hamas, Israel‚Äôs right wing government has imposed an unlawful siege on Gaza and its civilian population ‚Äì no food, no water, no electricity, no supplies, while knowingly bombing a densely populated civilian area,  causing arbitrary, indiscriminate death and suffering. We condemn these violations of international law unequivocally. 

All attacks against civilians are prohibited by international law, regardless of who commits them or why.

To achieve a lasting and just peace in the region, the structure of trauma and violence must end and the parties must return to good faith negotiations based on international law and UN resolutions. All Palestinians and Israelis, and particularly the children of both nations, are entitled to safety and security. The prolonged Israeli occupation of Palestine ‚Äì the longest in the modern world ‚Äì must end completely and immediately, and Palestinian self-determination must be realized.

We express our solidarity with Israeli and Palestinian civilians alike and amplify the voices of those calling for an immediate ceasefire.

A heartbreaking call between a father and his daughter has emerged amid the escalating Israel-Hamas conflict that has killed nearly 3,000 people since October 7 - the day Palestine-based Hamas group launched their murderous invasion of Israel. 

The daughter was at the Supernova music festival when the Hamas terrorists sprayed the thousands of revellers, most of them young adults, with gunfire as they escaped by car and fled through an open field.

"Please send the police, urgently!!!" the girl is heard saying in Hebrew.

"I am sending them. Mami, Calm down. Stay with me on the line. Don't get offline, okay?" her father replies to her desperate appeal.

"Be quiet," he adds.

"They are crushing me," she replies, the fear palpable in her voice.

"Be quiet Mami. Stay crushed," the father says.

"Yuvali, my daughter. Take a deep breath, hide. Act dead," he adds.

"Injured outside? Explain the situation to me," he tells her.

The girl replies, "Dead bodies over me."

"Wait, are the terrorists still there," he asks her.

"Circling around. Dad, send the police," she says in a trembling voice.

"Yuvali, act dead. Hang up the call. Act dead," he tells her.

In another audio, the girl is heard telling her mother that she is alive.

"Please tell our family that I am alive and I love them to the infinity. Mom, I want to stay alive. Please let them (police) come," she says.

The audio call gives a sense of the nightmare that innocent people faced on October 7 as Hamas men went on a rampage in Israeli towns. 

Supernova music festival, an all-night rave near Kibbutz Re‚Äôim on the Gaza border, was one of the first targets after Hamas's murderous invasion of Israel on October 7. By the end of the massacre, 260 people were murdered.

 Others were captured by the attackers or wounded by the gunfire. Missiles rained down on the area throughout the attack.

Culloden is a powerfully emotive and atmospheric battlefield, the site of one of the most harrowing battles in Britain.

The Battle of Culloden marked a tragic end for the 1745 Jacobite Rising. In less than an hour, 1,600 men were slain ‚Äì 1,500 of them Jacobites.

Jacobites took their last stand at Culloden, fighting to reclaim the throne for the Stuarts. They fought to restore the exiled James VIII, and were led by Prince Charles Edward Stuart, James' son. George II‚Äôs government army, led by his son, the Duke of Cumberland, was equally determined to stop this happening.

The richly researched, stimulating and sensitive Culloden Visitor Centre, which stands beside the battlefield, features artefacts from both sides of the battle and interactive displays that reveal the background to the conflict. It's both a monument and a guide to a pivotal day in history.

#Outlander fans will also recognise the battlefield from early seasons of the hit series starring @samheughan and @caitrionabalfe.

This prayer of St. Francis asks for guidance in becoming an instrument of peace. The prayer emphasizes the importance of spreading love, forgiveness, faith, hope, light, and joy in places where there is hatred, injury, doubt, despair, darkness, and sadness. It also encourages selflessness and reminds us that by giving and pardoning, we receive and are pardoned.

The unfortunate reality of war is that no one truly wins in such conflicts because innocent civilians bear the brunt of the suffering while their leaders often remain safe and protected. 

This perspective sheds light on the unequal distribution of consequences during times of war, where those in power are shielded from the direct impact.  We need to address this disparity to have a deeper understanding of the true costs of war and the need for greater accountability and protection for innocent civilians caught in the crossfire.

Terrorism is a crime against humanity, whatever the cause, it is not the answer to conflict. 

I join in prayer with the energy of all the mothers from Israel, Palestine, and all over the world to stop all attacks against innocent people who woke up to this nightmare.  May peace reign in the hearts of all inhabitants of this planet.  We must be better than our ancestors. Blessings to all of the heroes and heroines who understand this message and are protecting all innocents on both sides of this conflict.  #nomorebloodshed #nomorehatredüö´ #love #peace #everychildrenareourchildren #peacetoisraelüáÆüá± #peacetopalestineüáµüá∏ #weareone

Post from Tara Mandala: The recent outbreak of conflict between Israel and Hamas is part of an ongoing war where thousands of people are being killed or held hostage. Today, and historically, the amount of death, displacement, and suffering, is inconceivable and devastating. 

We call on you to send prayers, blessings, and practice to this area of the world.

Green Tara practice and mantra is an important practice to be doing right now. You may also do the mantra and practice of the 13th Tara, Dr√∂lma Y√ºll√© Gyaljema, who protects all beings from war and violence, preventing destruction caused by anger and aggression (more info below).

The practice of Green Tara: Imagine yourself as Green Tara, who is seated with one leg in meditation, and one leg stretched out to swiftly respond to those in need. Imagine green light radiating out from her heart, and from the mantra which circles around her heart. Imagine this green light going out to all of those impacted by the war in Israel and Gaza, and helping those who have passed and those who are alive and suffering - bringing healing, shelter, food, clothing, and all forms of relief.

The mantra of Green Tara is:
OM TARE TUTTARE TURE SWAHA

Please also help in other ways. Our meditation needs to be supported by real-world activity.

We thank you for your practice.

~ With Blessings,
Tara Mandala

Text in graphic: Cherished community, thank you for being in this space. We know so many are hurting deeply as a result of the events of this past week; we see you and our hearts pour out to you. We mourn the senseless loss of innocent lives in this ongoing conflict.

We apologize if our silence appeared to be indifference. We still struggle to find the words to express how we feel. We acknowledge we are not fully equipt to speak on the enormity and nuances of this situation. We are fortunate to have found a number of voices articulating much of what we are feeling and hearing. We are sharing these posts in our stories in hope that they will resonate with you as they do with us.

I‚Äôm turning off comments on this post because I‚Äôm do not feel qualified to moderate a discussion on this difficult topic. You are welcome to reach out to me via DM or to our DEI committee via email at dei@knitcollage.com.

Gusto nya nag mamahalan at nag tutulungan tayo lahat. Kaya keep the faith and stay strong kasi si yza andyn lang nag iintercede kay God para bigyan tayo ng wisdom and strength. I love you and all of your children. Yza knows that and ganon din sya sa mga pinsan nya mahal na mahal nya. Ngyon continue natin legacy nya. Ung faith na and dedication na meron sya kay God and ung kagandahan ng puso nya at love na meron sya sa pamilya natin lahat. ‚Ä¢ A checkered game board with 64 squares corresponds to the mandala, an image that appears in many cultures and often represents intricate, repeating patterns. ‚Ä¢ The chessboard is the extension of a diagram formed by four squares. Considered as a mandala of Shiva, a popular Hindu deity, it represents the field of action of all the vital forces in the universe that Shiva controls and maintains.

‚Ä¢ In an early Hindu form of the game there were four players ‚Äì one for each of the four sides of the board.

‚Ä¢ Fate, as well as logic, had its say in the outcome of the game: at some point participants would roll the dice to determine the order of the moves. In Lewis Carroll‚Äôs Through the Looking-Glass, Alice finds herself in an alternative world ‚Äú‚Äòmarked out just like a large chessboard!‚Äô Alice said‚Ä¶ ‚ÄòIt‚Äôs a great huge game of chess that‚Äôs being played ‚Äì all over the world‚Ä¶‚Äô‚Äù Chess represents a combination of, or the eternal conflict between, good and evil, light and darkness, sense and passion. The very alternation of black and white in the chessboard squares is a symbol of fate bestowing, in turn, gifts and sorrows. This idea finds its way into the painting with horses at loggerheads in the background and knights fighting fiercely in the name of the king in the foreground. Fancy towers with unending tops represent the unlimited power of imagination.

New school! Operations on the ground have started to open an Academy School for vulnerable and displaced children in Aden, on the same model as Still I Rise Schools in DRC and North-West Syria. 

Why Yemen? In Yemen, the education crisis is dire. Approximately 2.7 million children lack access to education, facing violence, abuse, child labor, and recruitment into armed groups.

Since 2014, Yemen has experienced a conflict between Houthi rebels and the internationally recognized government. Amidst this turmoil, vital infrastructure, like schools and hospitals, were destroyed. Geopolitical rivalries and proxy interests have further inflamed the situation. 

The number of people who died due to the conflict is estimated to be 377,000, with over half of these fatalities occurring indirectly due to factors like famine and restricted healthcare access.

By the year 2022, a staggering count of 16.2 million individuals‚Äîsurpassing half of the entire population‚Äîwere grappling with acute food scarcity. Alongside this, approximately 4.3 million Yemenis have been forced to relocate within the country's borders due to the ongoing crisis.

The country's economy is in ruins, with homes, farms, and crucial civilian infrastructure destroyed.  The flow of food, heavily reliant on imports, is severely disrupted by the warring factions. Prices are soaring, and many of the poorest have lost their income.

The current humanitarian crisis in Yemen has increased the vulnerability of children and women to exploitation, violence and abuse, child labour, killing and maiming, recruitment and use of children by parties to the conflict as combatants. 

In addition to this, conflict and economic deterioration have compromised people‚Äôs access to health facilities. More than 80% of Yemen‚Äôs population struggles to have safe drinking water and adequate health services. 

After more than 9 years, Yemen remains one of the the world‚Äôs worst humanitarian crises. That is why we choose to open our school here! Stay tuned for more updates!

Different Levels of Integration in Integral Yoga 

According to Sri Aurobindo a person has many sides to his personality, each of which is to be expressed, but in view of their discordant movements, each comes in the way of others when they are expressed through mind. This is a big problem in the way of constructive development of the whole personality. In a letter to a disciple, Sri Aurobindo identified a variety of different personalities that expressed themselves in this person's life. These included a vital personality, a psycho-vital personality, a personality of a poet, musician and seeker of beauty, a mental-vital personality, a physical-mental personality, and a mental emotional personality. His vital personality aimed at success and became engaged with it after getting it, ignoring other aspects of his personality. The vital personality sought engagement of a deeper kind and suggested that it would be well to give up the other personalities. The psycho-vital personality was that of a vaishnava that wanted the Divine (Krisna), Bhakti and Ananda. The personality of the poet and musician tried to satisfy its emotional urges through works of art. The mental-vital personality was approving of Vairagya and Nirvana and insisted on a grim struggle of Tapasya when it saw that the vital personality stood in the way. The physical-mental personality was an extrovert and skeptical. The mental-emotional personality had strong belief in the Divine, Yoga, Bhakti and Guruvada. We see from this example how each of us is composed of many different personalities with differing tendencies, often in conflict with one another. 

Integral Yoga is an attempt to harmonize these personalities and to bring about a complete development of the whole personality of a person. It does not encourage the growth of one type of personality at the cost of other types. But this harmonization cannot be done from outside, and it cannot be done by the ordinary mind and vital mind because they are sure to bungle the affair. It can be done only from within by the spirit, who is the ultimate controller.

Our most powerful response to the horror in Israel and Palestine is to refuse to surrender our humanity. 
You will be told by some: The deaths of Israeli children are unfortunate but inevitable, because Israel‚Äôs occupation of Palestine is brutal and wrong.
You will be told by others: The deaths of Palestinian children are unfortunate but inevitable, because it is the only way to keep Israel safe from terror, and Hamas brought this on its own people. 
Both will say: Our aggression is the only response to their aggression, our fear more justified than their fear, our grief more devastating than theirs ever will be. 
But oh my love, the hierarchy of pain is the old way. The moment we allow our hearts to go numb is the moment we shut down our humanity. 
I don‚Äôt know the solution to the conflict in Israel and Palestine, but I do know the starting point: To grieve ‚Äútheir‚Äù children as our children. 
It‚Äôs the only way to break the cycle. 
To my loved ones who are Israeli, Jewish, and Palestinian: I see your searing pain. I love you and grieve with you and am reciting my ancestors‚Äô prayers for protection as you search for your families and bear the unbearable. May love find you through the impossible. 
To all of us witnessing this story: What does love want you to do? 
If you cannot look at the news and the images: It‚Äôs okay. Step away, be with the earth, go to the trees, let them breathe through you; remember that you don‚Äôt need to do all the things, just the one that‚Äôs yours to do. 
If you want to help but don‚Äôt know how: Begin in relationship. Who in your life is hurting from this? Offer to walk with them, listen to them. There is no fixing grief, only bearing it together. Only then do we know what to do next. 
If you are falling apart: Your breathlessness is not a sign of your weakness, but of your strength. Of how deeply you feel the horror, how deeply you care. You still feel. And that matters in a world that wants us to feel nothing. Who can feel it with you? breathe with you?

‚ÄúThe Myth of Redemptive Violence is the story of the victory of order over chaos by means of violence. It is the ideology of conquest, the original religion of the status quo. The gods favour those who conquer. Conversely, whoever conquers must have the favour of the gods.

Peace through war, security through strength: these are the core convictions that arise from this ancient historical religion, and they form the solid bedrock on which the Domination System is founded in every society.

When the good guy finally wins, viewers are then able to reassert control over their own inner tendencies, repress them, and re-establish a sense of goodness without coming to any insight about their own inner evil. The villain‚Äôs punishment provides catharsis; one forswears the villain‚Äôs ways and heaps condemnation on him in a guilt-free orgy of aggression. Salvation is found through identification with the hero.

No other religious system has even remotely rivaled the myth of redemptive violence in its ability to catechise its young so totally. From the earliest age, children are awash in depictions of violence as the ultimate solution to human conflicts. Nor does saturation in the myth end with the close of adolescence. There is no rite of passage from adolescent to adult status in the national cult of violence‚Ä¶

Not all shows for children or adults are based on violence, of course. Reality is far more complex than the simplicities of this myth, and maturer minds will demand more subtle, nuanced, complex presentations

Redemptive violence gives way to violence as an end in itself. It is no longer a religion that uses violence in the pursuit of order and salvation, but one in which violence has become an aphrodisiac, sheer titillation, an addictive high, a substitute for relationships. "Silent Screams"
Theme- Parental conflicts
.
Witnessing parents fighting in front of children can leave deep scars on their hearts and minds. Let's create a peaceful and loving environment for our little ones. 

constant exposure to parental conflict can cause significant emotional distress for children. They may feel anxious, scared, or overwhelmed by the tension and hostility in their environment. 

Children who grow up in an environment filled with constant fighting may also struggle with communication and conflict resolution skills, leading to challenges in their own relationships later in life. 

Children may blame themselves for their parents' arguments, believing that they are the cause of the conflict. This can lead to feelings of guilt, shame, and a distorted sense of self-worth. 

In conclusion, parents fighting in front of children can have devastating effects on their emotional well-being and overall development. It is crucial for parents to create a safe and nurturing environment for their children, where conflicts are resolved peacefully and respectfully.

I‚Äôm fighting the urge - born from fatigue, overwhelm, and the stress of injustice - to live in avoidance, to duck my head, to cloak my heart, to do or say nothing in the face of suffering and injustice. 

Before speaking, I paused. I read. I listened. I prayed. I‚Äôm praying. I felt. I‚Äôm feeling.

I mourn the loss of life. I grieve for those who have lost. I try to empathize with those hurting. I wince at the pain of children. 

I resist the temptation to compare suffering. I pray for peace in the Holy Land and peace in peoples‚Äô bodies. 

I also bear witness to the truth: an occupier and an occupied. 

I do not ignore the continuing, decades long occupation of Palestinian people by Israel that paints the backdrop of this moment. 

I do not selectively or naively condemn conduct without acknowledging this context.

I understand that violence begets violence. That hurt people hurt people. 

That dehumanization will be met with resistance. That resistance doesn‚Äôt always look perfect or feel palatable. That resistance causes trauma because it‚Äôs born from trauma. 

That the lines between aggression & self-defense unfortunately get blurry. That innocent or civilian can sadly become relative terms in the context of an ongoing occupation and conflict. It‚Äôs a tragic, unrelenting kill or be killed ecosystem that produces pain abound for all peoples.

That this occupation - unless acknowledged & interrupted - will perpetually produce a cycle of violence, inhumanity, and insecurity. 

So I stand on the side of peace. of safety. of justice. of dignity. of life. of love. of liberation.

And I know that to achieve those realities for all people we must start with manifesting that reality for the Palestinian people.

For several days now, we have been living in pain, in confusion, in a painful sense of helplessness that makes us fragile, vulnerable, disoriented, and above all, deeply saddened. For there is nothing more contagious than the pain of innocent men, women, old people and children. The horror of innocent humans brutally torn from their loved ones, beaten, imprisoned, tortured and diabolically terrorized is something that tears at the heart of anyone with a heart capable of beating for their fellow man. As parents, how can we not put ourselves in the shoes of those parents whose children's fate is unknown to them! As human beings, how can we not feel the dramatic echo of so much suffering! As human beings, where can we find hope, optimism, joy of life, when so much of our unfortunate humanity can go? Yet each of us knows in his conscience that every conflict, from the most trivial to the most bitter, is always and only an intellectual accident. We all know the weapons with which we could avoid their tragic consequences. What prevents us from using them? As people of faith, we pray with all our hearts that this will end as soon as possible; that everyone will be able to reunite with their loved ones and return to their homes. Let us pray. Let us pray with contrite hearts, with consistency and intensity, hoping in our hearts that this will end soon.

‚öîÔ∏èOne of the latest things I've discovered in Byzantine history was the conflict between a band of Kievan Rus' troops and the Byzantines in 1024 when the Byzantine Empire was at a time of peace and prosperity. In 1024, just a year before the great emperor Basil II's death (1025)- where my game is set in- a small conflict broke out in Byzantium when 800 Rus' warriors led by a certain Chrysocheir sailed to Byzantium to enlist in the legendary Varangian Guard. Unfortunately, the only source that discusses this conflict is the history of John Skylitzes who mentions that in 1024, a Rus' leader namer Chrysocheir sailed with 800 men to Constantinople to enlist in the Varangian Guard of Emperor Basil II. It is also noted that Chrysocheir was a relative of the late Kievan Rus' prince Vladimir, the brother-in-law of Basil II; although Chrysocheir was probably a Greek translation of his name whereas his real name remains unknown though it could be derived from the Old Norse Audmundr. 
*
üåä When in Constantinople, Chrysocheir and his men were asked to surrender their weapons before entering the city to enlist. Chrysocheir however refused to surrender his weapons and so he and his men sailed south into the Marmara Sea and into the Aegean after defeating a Byzantine fleet at the Dardanelles. The Rus' then set themselves up in the Greek island of Lemnos where they were eventually confronted by a larger Byzantine fleet led by the Strategos of the Samos Theme David of Ohrid and troops from Thessaloniki led by the general Nikephoros Kabasilas. The Byzantine commanders initially pretended to negotiate with the Rus' and so the Rus' fell for it only for the Byzantines to suddenly trap the Rus' and kill them all including their leader Chrysocheir. SEEKING THE ULTIMATE TRUTH ‚ù§Ô∏èüñ§üíö

Self-knowledge is true knowledge‚Äîall other knowledge changes. What we learn in school differs based on the period of time. Our school knowledge is not based on what's good for us but rather on the best way to govern and control others.

That's why some communities send their children to two schools‚Äîone to learn about others, the other to learn about themselves. So, with all that we think we know, such as the name of the first president, sadly, we don't know who we are. We've spent years believing in the intellect and not the spirit. As a result, we stay child-like, superficially smart, and uninvolved instead of wise and evolved.

With self-knowledge, we become empowered with thoughts that transcend this world. We seek that ultimate truth. But to seek that truth, we must realize the conflict within ourselves.

That conflict is to either remain asleep or wake up. As the story goes, we can be like "Iai," an ass that won't let go of the lies or falsehood. Undoubtedly, we've become stubborn in thinking that the path is one of assimilation with a dominant force, whereas it's one of assimilating with a life force. No one will empower you with self-knowledge, which leads us to the "ultimate" truth. Give yourself the gift of waking up to truly being free. -Dr. Robbin Alston

Photography does not automatically lend itself to narrative. Building a story arc with individual pictures requires a sense of time, place, character, and causality. This is a photo essay that I did in 2005 for the New York Times Magazine about a road being built in impovrished rural Nepal by Maoist guerrillas using conscripted labour. In this case, I used black-and-white film and a classic linear story arc. The images attempt to distill a complex series of events during a long-running conflict into a tight narrative. We will be discussing the relationship between photography and narrative at my upcoming workshop at @domainecazenac in #Dordogne, France in mid-November. We wish to express our utmost solidarity with victims of war who face unjust suffering and attack. We stand with the Palestinian people of Gaza, West Bank, and Jordan, as well as those in refugee camps and the wider diaspora displaced globally who are still awaiting their right of return. We support the Palestinian struggle for liberation and autonomy from the settler apartheid state of Israel that has brutally oppressed their community and other dissenters for many decades, and we condemn Israel‚Äôs bombardment of Gaza and the blockade that deprives Palestinians of basic necessities like food, water, and fuel. We recognize that political parties and governments are not representative of either Palestinian or Jewish peoples. 

As an educational space, we advise being wary and critical of disinformation that aims to create selective outrage and division rather than building towards peace. Occupation, colonization and land theft are the root causes of conflict in Palestine. Direct action, and political resistance to settler violence is necessary. The dehumanization and targeting of vulnerable civilians is always unjustified and we reject any defense of it. It is grossly insensitive to advocate for war crimes in the privilege and comfort of our homes in Canada, and far away from facing the ensuing dangers. We have people in our collective who have experienced trauma and loss from occupation, war and resistance activism, and who have had their lives permanently altered in ways that many of us cannot imagine. We also have Jewish anarchists who are staunchly anti-zionist, and are committed to a free and just Palestine for everyone. We extend our compassion and sympathy for all innocent lives lost. We will continue to advocate for solutions that support liberating Palestinians from colonial violence, and providing peaceful co-existence for all civilians.

Much love to everyone who is deeply affected by these events, and may we continue to hold strong the ideas of liberation, freedom and equity for all.

Water has long been used as a tactical weapon in warfare

The pummelling of Gaza and the destruction of its water systems by Israel is only the latest instance of water being used as a weapon of war

Experts and leaders will soon come together in their thousands at the first¬†UN conference dedicated to water¬†in nearly half a century.

At the conference, which begins on March 22 in New York, delegates will no doubt stress that ‚Äúwater is life‚Äù. And it‚Äôs true: water nourishes, cleanses and even inspires the poetry and painting so desperately needed by our modern and rushed society. We really cannot live without it.

But as a professor of water security who focuses on its role in conflict, I know that water is death, too. And I don‚Äôt just mean the awesome destructive force of floods ‚Äì hundreds of children in Pakistan and twice as many adults drowned when a ‚Äúmonsoon on steroids‚Äù burst the banks of the Indus River last summer ‚Äì or agonising spells of drought.

I mean the way we use water in war ‚Äì or more specifically, as a tool towards violent political or military objectives, when water becomes a tactical weapon and a strategic battlefield resource. At the UN conference, delegates have a chance to begin to put a stop to this. But before we change our behaviour, we must first reflect on it.
