The intractable Israeli-Palestinian conflict and its latest unimaginable horrors has shaken us all to the core. The pain from the brutality of the circumstances, like a vice around our hearts, is inescapable, no matter the affiliation. It is hard to contain emotions. 

Muhammad Deif and his Hamas butchers can only be qualified as inhuman. Who else would inflict such indiscriminate loss of life on religious and political grounds? To call them animals is an insult to all species. 

As we collectively mourn this ongoing tragedy, we must also try to understand the source of this dehumanized indoctrination in order to correct it. A few things come to mind. 

People rarely turn into killing machines in a vacuum. The Hamas leadership must be eradicated, sure, but what does that mean? Without a change in policy and a philosophical commitment to humanizing relationships on both sides, despite the historical hardships, is it reasonable to expect a different outcome? 

Netanyahu has been in power for 16 years and his myopic leadership is at least in part responsible for the utter failure to prevent this tragedy. 

Hamas, on the other hand, has been ruling Gaza since the last elections, 18 years ago. In a survey conducted in 2021, the authoritarian government received merely 30% approval from its population. It is hard to imagine that number not plummeting given the scope of this ongoing destruction, inclusive of innocent Palestinians. 

To imagine peace we must refrain from retributive impulses; we must wipe the slate clean. Mandela and Gandhi taught us the value of forgiveness in the spirit of humanizing the peace process. 

Let us see in this tragedy an opportunity to usher in new leadership‚Äîon both sides‚Äîand reinvent a diplomatic coexistence based on shared values of peace and prosperity for all. Concessions must be made and a commitment to teach love rather than hate. Because the guttural pain of loss hurts universally. And we must forgive before more deaths escalate. 

As Buddha teaches, holding onto anger Is like drinking poison and expecting the other person to die. We stand with Israel and innocent Palestinians. We stand with peace.

As a wedding planner, I've long been captivated by the deep symbolism embodied in the chuppah. In these recent days, amid moments of shock and sorrow, I'm struck by how its significance resonates even more deeply. It stands not just as a testament to love but as a powerful symbol of hope and unity during this time of darkness.

With its delicate canopy, the chuppah serves as a sanctuary where two hearts become one, pledging to embark on a shared journey of love, understanding, and resilience. It is a physical manifestation of unity, a shelter under which vows are exchanged, dreams are woven, and futures are built. 

In this symbolic space, love blossoms, and hope thrives, reminding us of the unyielding strength of unity. Just as the chuppah represents the unbreakable bond between two individuals, we, too, can create a haven of compassion, empathy, and solidarity where the warmth of our hearts can conquer the darkness of despair. Amid the chaos, our love becomes the canopy under which we stand, unwavering and united. Like the threads of a tallit, prayers weave a tapestry of hope, resilience, and peace. 

We support Israel, our Jewish clients, colleagues, and friends, holding onto the strength of togetherness, just as the loving hands of the surrounding community uphold the pillars of a chuppah. Our steadfast support extends to all those affected by this tragic conflict, including the innocent civilians of Palestine. Our commitment echoes in our unwavering love and continuous prayers, and we unequivocally condemn and reject Hamas, terrorism, violence, and antisemitism. 

May the symbolism of the chuppah remind us that even in the face of adversity and deep despair, hope will shelter, love will prevail, and unity will triumph.

In response to the Middle East tensions, investors have turned to gold, which is considered a safe haven asset during uncertain times.

Hyderabad: Gold rates in Hyderabad have rebounded, reversing the declining trend of the past few days. This reversal in trend is attributed to the tensions in the Middle East region due to the Israel-Palestine conflict.

In response to the Middle East tensions, investors have turned to gold, which is considered a safe haven asset during uncertain times.

Current gold rates in Hyderabad
At present, the rates of gold in Hyderabad stand at Rs 54,000 for 10 grams of 22-carat gold and Rs 58,910 for 24-carat gold.

Recently, the price of gold hit a six-month low, with rates for 10 grams of 22-carat and 24-carat gold dropping to Rs 52,600 and Rs 57,380, respectively.

Although the price of gold has increased by over 2.6 percent from the six-month low, jewelry shops in Hyderabad are witnessing a rush, as many anticipate that prices may rise further.

Israel-Palestine Conflict
The recent tensions in the Middle East were sparked by Hamas attacks that resulted in the deaths of hundreds of Israelis and injuries to many.

In response to these attacks, Israel launched airstrikes against the Gaza Strip, claiming that the attacks were targeting Hamas infrastructure. These airstrikes have also resulted in the deaths of hundreds and injuries to many.

Due to the escalation of tension in the Middle East region, investors are concerned about volatility in global markets and have turned to gold, causing the rates of the yellow metal to rise not only in Hyderabad but also in other Indian cities and around the world.

Alex Younger, who served as the head of the UK's foreign intelligence service from 2014 to 2020, gave his comments in an interview on the BBC's "The Today Podcast."

It came after Hamas fighters stormed into Israel and massacred whole villages ‚Äî Israel has said more than 1,000 people were killed, including children and the elderly.

He said: "I absolutely understand and endorse Israel's right to defend themselves in the circumstances, and indeed to restore the credibility of those defenses, so that that sense of psychological safety can be restored to the people."

"But here's the thing, you shouldn't do what your enemy wants you to do," said Younger.

Israel launched waves of airstrikes on Gaza in the wake of the attacks, killing hundreds. It has massed troops on the border of the Gaza Strip and pledged to destroy Hamas in its entirety, but has yet to move in its troops. 

"And it's really obvious now that Hamas are essentially laying a trap for Israel," said Younger.

"And [it] will be well pleased if Israel commits itself to an open-ended, full-scale ground invasion of Gaza because of the scale and intensity of conflict that that would entail, and the loss of innocent life that would inevitably follow and the radicalization that would engender, and the extent to which will put Israel's allies and partners in the region in an impossible position."

He said Hamas was likely surprised by how successful its mission had been, with militants successfully evading Israeli surveillance and breaking through Israel's high-tech border security before advancing around 30 kilometres into Israel. 

A senior Hamas official said much the same thing.

Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu pledged to destroy Hamas in the wake of the attacks. But analysts say that in invading Gaza, the densely populated region the militant group has governed since 2007, the IDF would face fierce resistance from Hamas, which is embedded in a network of underground tunnels and bases. Such an attack would likely result in the loss of thousands of civilian lives.

Over the years, MERCY Malaysia‚Äôs initiatives have manage to slightly reduce the affected people‚Äôs humanitarian burden, and help support them continue to live their life normally. However, the number of affected population and the needs for humanitarian, as well as development remains high in this conflict, which is one of the world‚Äôs longest continuing conflicts.

The relief aid distribution aimed to provide much-needed support to the people residing in the Gaza Strip, reaffirming MERCY Malaysia commitment to alleviating their suffering and promoting resilience within the community. Other live saving initiatives are being conducted, which include supply of medicines and providing fuels to operate ambulance as the conflict‚Äôs casualties have not been restricted to combatants, with a large number of civilian fatalities on both sides.

MERCY Malaysia is monitoring the humanitarian needs and impact, and looking at all possibilities to provide aid to support those in need of humanitarian assistance.

Many people go through life trying to find that one perfect person who will fulfill their every desire. ‚Å†

That person will like the same things as you, believe the same things as you, handle conflict with such ease and grace, and basically be everything you‚Äôve ever wanted. Once you FIND that person, love will be easy... right?‚Å†

We get tricked by our Hollywood obsessed culture into believing that this is what worthwhile love is and if there are any differences, triggers, or conflicts then that person is NOT ‚Äúthe one.‚Äù I used to believe that too.üíî‚Å†

But compatibility is built. Differences can create balance. Our strengths are in different areas and I love that.

Real Love is teamwork. It‚Äôs being able to appreciate rather than resent differences. It‚Äôs always choosing to be on each other‚Äôs side, rather than always needing things to be seen and done YOUR way. ‚Å†
‚Å†
üëâLove is a practice.‚Å†
‚Å†
üëâLove is a skill.‚Å†
‚Å†
üëâLove is built. Love is built. Love is built.‚Å†

I was so lucky to meet & get to know Palestinian activist @issaamro that evening (last photo). You can read all about him & his great work online. The old man in the photos is someone I do not feel lucky to know: David Wilder, who has for ages made himself a speaker for the settlers in that region. IDF had to step in David is so quick to instigate with hate. (He was born in NJ, by the way, you can read about him online. Many of the settlers are American!) Naively perhaps I still hope they have a happier life than many of us. I haven‚Äôt stopped having nightmares about war since my first taste of it as a toddler.

Today is #nationalcomingoutday and I‚Äôve debated if I wanted to *publicly* announce that I am bisexual, but I remember seeing someone‚Äôs post a few years ago and I remember how much it inspired me and made me feel less alone.

The Abou Dan family was holed up at home, in the Bureij camp in the center of the Gaza Strip. Everyone kept checking their phones to make sure that no message had been sent from the Israeli army telling them to evacuate their home. 

"There was no warning shot, no text message, nothing. All of a sudden, a bomb fell, then two," said Ahmed Abou Dan over the phone. By late afternoon on Monday, October 9, Gaza had been under intensive bombardment by Israeli fighter planes for almost 24 hours. 

This 43-year-old Palestinian was the only survivor of his siblings who, as is often the case in Gaza, lived in the same building. His son, his father, his two brothers and part of their family were killed. Fourteen people in all, including four children and two teenagers. One of his nieces was pregnant.

"So far, I've buried 10 martyrs, but four are still under the rubble. I'm moving heaven and earth. We extracted my brother's family. But my son, Walid, 22, is still under the rubble, as is my niece Amira, 16, and one of the children of another niece ‚Äì he was 7, I think. Isn't it despicable to have killed them?" he asked, his breath coming in angry gasps. 

27 people, including 15 minors, were killed on the day of the strike on the Abu Dan family's building in the Bureij camp and the surrounding localities, according to the count by Al-Mezan, the Palestinian Center for Human Rights, and Al-Haq, three Palestinian human rights NGOs. 

Ahmed Abou Dan realized it was a miracle he had survived: "It was very violent: The bombing destroyed our building, which is 35 meters high. Imagine a four-story building collapsing on you. I live on the third floor. Both walls fell on me. I was terrified. What can you feel at that moment? Fright. Fright! I recited my profession of faith."

In the face of the conflict in Israel and Palestine, our most powerful response is to refuse to surrender our humanity. Let compassion, empathy, and dialogue be our guiding stars toward lasting peace.

To our supporters and community, 

The harsh realities of conflict and violence cannot be taken lightly - and when the storm arrives, Team Stott heads into the direction of the danger. 

And no, it never gets easier. 

This current conflict in Israel is no different. 

We received a call from a family that needed immediate support to safely evacuate from the country and get their family out safely. 

In a matter of hours, Dean was on a flight and we had 18 families needing help. 

The number has now grown and we are now in the 100s.. 

We are self-funding this initiative because we knew we had to help. 

We had to run into the danger and do what we do best. 

We need money for flights, ground moves, local support and supplies. 

Over the years supporting Dean in his missions, I've seen so many people try to take advantage of him. They would try to throw him into danger zones while they reaped the rewards and benefits. 

I quickly became known as the "b*tch" of Team Stott; I would constantly block these people because I knew they only saw him as a commodity. 

To this day, my gut on this matter has never failed us. 

And right now my gut is telling me to reach out to our community and ask for your help.

BREAKING NEWS:
Stellantis and Korean battery powerhouse Samsung SDI have announced a joint venture to build a new $3.2 EV batter factory in Kokoma, Indiana.

WHAT HAPPENED:
This is actually the 2nd plant Stellantis and Samsung SDI are building together. effectively, the companies are more than doubling the production capacity of their first plant in Kokomo, Indiana. This second investment will get Kokomo up to around 67GWh of power produced every year. Depending on how you slice it, that's enough batteries for around 1 million EVs per year.

CURRENT STATUS:
This is a huge move that will give Stellantis a massive advantage moving forward. As an international company, Stellantis is getting hurt a little less by the ongoing UAW strikes. As such, they have the capital to make some big long-term investments right now. Lots of advanced battery manufacturers like Samsung SDI and LG Energy Solution are clamoring to partner with American firms in order to get access to IRA tax breaks. With Ford pausing their own EV battery plant, Stellantis is getting out to a solid lead here.

WHY IT MATTERS:
This announcement is going to make things a lot messier for Stellantis as they move forward with the negotiations they're having with the UAW. The autoworker's union announced a huge deal where a big GM battery plant will be staffed with UAW workers last week. Battery plants and pensions are a big part of the UAW's ongoing negotiations, so this announcement just opened up an entirely new front in the conflict between the UAW and Stellantis. For now, Stellantis still has enough comparative advantage to like this deal. Both Stellantis and Samsung SDI stock rose on the announcement.

As travelers, we arrive in places, sometimes with a knowledge of historical context and sometimes severely lacking it. Whether we have traveled long distances and to many countries, or just to a few places, we are citizens of not just our home countries but of the world around us.

It‚Äôs why we believe it is our responsibility as a community of travelers to speak up when we can; to use our voices to help others around us.

The history of conflict between Israel & Palestine has started long before our own lives. Some may tell us that this means we cannot or should not comment on what is happening, or form opinions. That our role as travelers is to accept things, listen, and be silent.

But there are things that we should all stand for, and speak against.

Ripping children from the arms of their parents and kidnapping them is not okay.
Lighting homes on fire is not okay.
The destruction of peaceful places of worship is not okay.
Sexual assault is not okay.
Murder and violence are not okay.
Taking hostages and endangering innocent lives is not okay.

We mourn for our Israeli friends who are fearing for their lives and their families, for the many who have been killed, and for the others who have unexpectedly been called to fight. 

We mourn for our Palestinian friends whose homes have been obliterated in Gaza, who have lost their lives in air strikes, and who are running low on life-saving resources.

We mourn the many years of desperate and passionate conflict that have led to this moment and many other violent moments before.

We believe in the importance of difficult dialogue, especially in impossible situations. In finding solutions that can create peace rather than destroy each other.

We beg for the violence to stop in Israel and Palestine, and around the world.

Our hearts ache knowing this pain and suffering is happening. As @valariekaur  stated, ‚ÄúThis is not about equivalency. The time has come to center the human cost of the conflict above all.‚Äù

ALL THIS WEEK, whilst people who profess to be of faith have sat in almighty judgement (with ZERO knowledge of works being undertaken behind the scenes with people of all faiths to stem more tides of ignorant, blind hate), beautiful souls continue to shine out from amidst the rubble & horror...

Friends of all faiths, met on my travels through the Holy Land just over 3 years ago, have been checking in, reaching out, and sharing the horrors they witnessed and must now survive.

One such piece of my heart is a Muslim teacher & mother I met in #Palestine - who is fearful her parents have been killed in the latest bombings & is also now having trouble breathing. 

Another is a Jewish grandfather in #Israel, who has spent 15 years secretly driving Palestinians stopped at checkpoints to hospitals, to ensure they were treated. One of his grandchildren is now missing.

Another is an Arab Christian, who is trying to aid anyone he can, at great risk to his own life. He hasn't been in touch for 2 days now, so am praying he's OK.

They are just three of many who bless my worlds. 

None of them supports any atrocity, injustice, or invasion committed in their name against others. No matter who is committing them or why.

In this supposed chess board of black and white, humans aren't.

One group who changed everything for me was the @theparentscircle. I travelled especially to learn of and meet with them, forged as they are of  Palestinian and Israeli parents who have each lost children to this conflict, and who refuse to let the world "take revenge" in the names of their children.

S/Heroes, every one.

And every day this week, despite the pain, fear, horror, headlines, sirens, bombs, & fury, every one of these friends, no matter what is happening around them, has been ending their messages to me with some form of: "Am praying for everyone innocent on the other side. Wish they knew."

So I'm letting you know.

That beyond the shattering headlines, words baying for dehumanisation and division, and lines drawn in man-made quicksand, are souls who will never bow to hate. Or any justification of it.

And therein lies hope.

As you were. X

Congrats to @reelguyana on the launch of their excellent new documentary the March onwards. The launch was held today at @movietowneguyana and examines the impact of farming development on the warrau who depend on crabs that dwell among the mangroves of the Barima Mora Passage in region 1. The Mangroves need to be felled in order to clear land for farming which causes the crabs to move. This migration makes it harder for the crabs to be caught by the Warrua thus affecting their livelihood. 

The film examines this conflict along with possible solutions including alternative means of income for the communities. 

It officially premiers across Guyana on the 15th October at 6:00 PM on all Reel Guyana channels. 

Visit Guyana is very proud of the work done by Alex Arjune and his sister Victoria and their team and is happy to support it. 

The March onwards is a gripping documentary that is heartfelt, honest and moving. Using stunning filmmaking and authentic storytelling, the documentary beautifully captures the essence of the changes along the Barima mora passage through the voices of the people who live there. Well done.

Robert ‚ÄúBob‚Äù Zaval of North Huntingdon, saw the horrors of war as an Army tank commander fighting in Europe during World War II.

‚ÄúBoy, it was tough. Your biggest thing was to stay alive,‚Äù said Zaval, who recently reflected on his long life before marking his 102nd birthday on Tuesday.

Like many other combat veterans, he does not consider himself a hero. He survived battles in Belgium, Holland, France, Germany and Yugoslavia.

‚ÄúThe real heroes are the ones who are still over there ‚Ä¶ who never came home,‚Äù Zaval said.

Zaval is one of a dwindling breed. Of the more than 16 million Americans who served in the military during World War II, the U.S. Department of Veteran Affairs estimates that only about 120,000 remain alive eight decades after the end of the conflict. Of the Pennsylvanians who served during that war, only about 7,030 were alive this year, according to the VA.

Zaval remains in the modest home he built on Lincoln Way, which he shares with his wife, Helene. He remains mentally sharp and uses a wheelchair to get around.

Zaval, who shortened his name from Zavalydriga, is the father of three children.

Zaval entered the ‚Äúreal world‚Äù after graduating from Norwin High School in 1939, part of the nation‚Äôs last class of high school graduates before war broke out in Europe in September 1939. With America on the sidelines of the conflict between Nazi Germany and England and France, Zaval landed a job as a steelworker at Fort Pitt Steel Casting Co. in McKeesport.

Anti-war sentiment grew in some segments of society, with an America First movement against any involvement in Europe‚Äôs war, but Zaval was not so certain the country would not be dragged into conflict.

‚ÄúI thought we would get involved,‚Äù Zaval said.

CHRISTIAN CONFLICT - THE PERILS OF PRIDE.

Pride and Haughtiness... 

The word haughty is defined by Merriam-Webster as ‚Äúblatantly and disdainfully proud.‚Äù The word is always used in The Bible in the evil sense of ‚Äúarrogant, disdainful and setting oneself above others‚Äù, it is often set in contrast to being humble.

When we are haughty, we become the center of our universe, everything revolves around us. There is little, if any, concern for what others think and no consideration to and of the will of God. Pride, haughtiness, is the trunk of the tree from which all other sins sprout. When we are at the center of our world, then nothing that we want is unlawful to us.

God is resistant to haughtiness. Over and over in Scripture, we read that God brings down the haughty and the proud (2 Samuel 2:28; Psalm 18:27; Isaiah 2:11, 5:15; Ezekiel 16:50). Twice in Proverbs, we read that haughtiness precedes destruction (16:18, 18:12). The New Testament is clear on the dangers of arrogance, warning repeatedly against it. Both James and Peter warn that God actively opposes the proud (James 4:6, 1 Peter 5:5).

The Bible tells us those who are arrogant and have a haughty heart are an abomination to Him: ‚ÄúEvery one that is proud in heart is an abomination to the LORD: though hand join in hand, he shall not be unpunished.‚Äù (Proverbs 16:5).

There are two Greek forms of the word arrogance used in the New Testament, essentially meaning the same. Huperogkos means ‚Äúswelling‚Äù or ‚Äúextravagant‚Äù as used in ‚Äúarrogant words‚Äù (2 Peter 2:18; Jude 1:16). The other is phusiosis, meaning a ‚Äúpuffing up of the soul‚Äù or ‚Äúloftiness, pride‚Äù (2 Corinthians 12:20). It is incumbent upon believers to recognize that being arrogant or having a pompous attitude is antithetical to godliness (2 Peter 1:5-7). Arrogance is nothing more than an overt display of one‚Äôs sense of self-importance (2 Timothy 3:2). It is akin to that ‚Äúit‚Äôs all about me‚Äù mindset that says, ‚ÄúThe world revolves around me‚Äù (Proverbs 21:24).üî•üö®üì¢

The "alienation industry" is the dark underbelly of the family court system it's a lucrative industry. We will shine a light into the darkness and provide a pathway for those who find themselves trapped in the predictable but disturbing pipeline.

From the National Safe Parents Organization, "The term "parental alienation" or "parental alienation syndrome (PAS)" was created by Richard Gardner in 1985 for the purpose of deflecting the court's attention from child abuse claims against fathers. This is a debunked concept, based on Gardner's clinical observations, not scientific data, and is not recognized by the United Nations (UN), American Psychiatric Association (APA), the World Health Organization (WHO) or the American Medical Association. Prior to his suicide, Gardner was an unpaid part time clinical professor of child psychiatry at the College of Physicians and Surgeons at Columbia University. He made his money mainly as a forensic expert on a foundation of disturbing views, discrediting women and children on the basis of his debunked parental alienation theories.‚Äù

The seeds planted by Gardner have grown into a lucrative cottage industry, perpetuated by unscrupulous professionals who are profiting off childhood trauma, much of which they are creating. Once a child is placed in the ‚Äúalienation pipeline,‚Äù it is a very predictable journey and often ends with the child being forced into traumatizing reunification therapy or worse, reunification camp. www.alienationindustry.com

Slow economic development has been a chronic and difficult concern for many countries throughout the world in recent years. When an economy's pace of expansion falls below its historical average or fails to reach its full potential, this phenomenon happens.

Slow economic growth can result in a reduced standard of living for the population. When an economy fails to expand at a sufficient rate, incomes may stagnate, and opportunities for advancement become limited.

Additionally, sluggish economic growth often translates into higher unemployment rates and underemployment, as businesses may be less inclined to hire or expand during uncertain economic conditions.

And of course, governments may face fiscal challenges as tax revenues stagnate while social spending needs rise. This can lead to budget deficits and, in some cases, unsustainable levels of debt, amongst other macroeconomic complexities such as political and social unrest.

According to the World Bank's September Africa Pulse report, economic activity in Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA) is expected to slow further from 3.6 percent in 2022 to 2.5 percent in 2023, a 0.6 percentage point decrease from the April 2023 prediction.

According to the research, 28 of the 48 Sub-Saharan African countries' growth predictions for 2023 have been revised lower.

Some of the factors that have contributed to the downward trend include monetary and fiscal policy tightness in response to high inflation and fiscal unsustainability, high risk of debt distress, structural constraints such as energy and transportation bottlenecks, and rising conflict and violence manifested in a series of events such as coup d‚Äô√©tats, protests, and heightened social unrest across Sub-Saharan African countries.

While some countries have managed to thrive and record impressive economic growth in 2023 so far, some have not been so fortunate. Based on the report, here are the top 10 African countries with the lowest economic growth in 2023 so far

In order to understand events - as the one now in Gaza and Israel - it is very important always to return to the origin, that is, the inception of this conflict. For those of us who believe in art's ability to save us, Jane Frere's @janegfrere renowned installation the "Return of the Soul: The Nakba Project ," (2007-2008) is a perfect example. This work consists of approximately seven thousand miniature human figures representing the Nakba catastrophe, that is, the ethnic cleansing of Palestine in 1948. Each wax figure is the same light yellow color, but they diminish in size (from twenty-two centimeters to half a centimeter), creating the illusion of a crowd receding into the distance. They are all suspended by transparent nylon from the roof of the gallery and face the same way. These figures were not made by Frere; instead, she taught Palestinian art groups how to make them in a series of workshops in refugee camps. The installation is accompanied by written testimonies and audio and video recordings of interviews with families expelled during the establishment of the state of Israel. These are accounts of loss, fear, and hope of return. Frere‚Äôs installation gives voice to these stories but also presents the essential emergency that has been concealed by their silence: the ongoing denial of the ethnic cleansing. The Nakba is still not recognized as a major historical event, even though Palestinians are still suffering its consequences in refugee camps throughout the Middle East. Let‚Äôs hope this violence will end today, now! Frere's work is among the 12 works of great artists I included in my book "Why Only Art can Save Us" @columbiauniversitypress -  now translated in Italian by @politiseganfreddo - where absent emergencies are disclosed. Learn more about Jane work in her website here: www.https://janefrere.info/

Prada, kruising springer spaniel/stafford, kwam bij ons binnen via een inbeslagname, samen met haar mama. Ze zit momenteel in een opvanggezin.

Het opvanggezin beschrijft Prada als zijnde een actieve puber. Ze is lief, enthousiast en een grote knuffelkont. Ze geniet van de buitenlucht, loopt graag rond in de tuin tussen de andere honden (bordercollies) en vond snel haar plaatsje in het gezin. Ze is intussen zindelijk geworden, gaat zelf naar buiten om haar behoeftes te doen. Een ongelukje ‚Äôs nachts is wel nog mogelijk. 

Alleen blijven is toch wel een probleem. Het is dan ook erg belangrijk gericht kauwmateriaal (bijvoorbeeld olijfwortelstok, een oude schoen, ‚Ä¶) achter te laten waar ze mee kan spelen. 

üê∂ Prada wordt bij voorkeur geplaatst als enige hond. Ze begrijpt de signalen die de andere honden geven niet altijd, durft hierbij ook uitdagen en zal een conflict niet uit de weg gaan. 
üê±üê∞ Er zijn ook katten in het gezin: hierbij is het opletten geblazen. Daarom plaatsen we Prada bij voorkeur in een gezin zonder katten. 
üë∂ Prada houdt NIET van kinderen: ze blaft ernaar en drijft ze in een hoekje. Bij het uitstrekken van een hand bijvoorbeeld, zal ze ernaar happen. 

üëâ Prada is een jonge puber die nog heel wat kan bijleren. Hiervoor zal heel wat tijd en geduld ge√Ønvesteerd dienen te worden. Daarom zoeken wij adoptanten, zonder kinderen, en bij voorkeur ook zonder andere dieren, die het grootste deel van de dag, bij haar kunnen zijn en haar liefdevol en met duidelijke regels en afspraken kunnen opvoeden. Prada zal zich dan verder ontwikkelen als een fantastisch hondje die zich ‚Äôs avonds, knus naast (op) u zal installeren om mee te genieten van de huiselijke sfeer.

the five of cups can be a tough card to see. so many RWS-based interpretations view this card as only overwhelming grief, devastation, an inability to process hard feelings or move beyond loss. and indeed, fives in general are associated with friction and conflict, with breakthroughs that may require us to move beyond something established and safe. yet five also represents freedom, adventure, being true to the self. the suit of cups is not only about the hardest emotions we can think of. and with the five of cups, as @thetarotlady so generously reminds us in her new book the cards you‚Äôre dealt, ‚Äúwhat seems like failure may be an overlooked opportunity.‚Äù sometimes we simply need to broaden our perspective. 
.
the sun as a clarifying card both confirms and deepens this message. as an archetype the sun is both generous and restorative, a reminder that even if things feel hard right now, there are powerful shifts at work. what is brightening? what is revealing itself? what are you discovering, embracing, integrating? what unexpected changes in relationships or emotions are actually creating opportunities for pleasure, connection, deeper joy?
.
today, show yourself kindness, even if part of your mind or heart keeps whispering that you don‚Äôt deserve it. the world is hard enough without us being cruel to ourselves, too. how can you hold space for difficult emotions? how can you accept support when it‚Äôs offered? how can you celebrate the victories and progress you‚Äôve made, even if you aren‚Äôt fully finished yet? and in grieving the loss of human life, the callous ways that so many marginalized groups are treated in the united states and around the world, how can you commit to kindness, generosity, and empathy whenever possible?
.

The Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe (PACE) adopted a resolution calling on the governments of the 5 Council of Europe members to fully investigate all cases of the use of ‚ÄúPegasus‚Äù and other spy programs and provide information on them within three months.
Azerbaijan, Poland, Hungary, Greece and Spain are among the five members mentioned in the resolution.
Citing a series of journalistic and research projects that revealed and confirmed the use of ‚ÄúPegasus‚Äù, ‚ÄúCandiru‚Äù and ‚ÄúPredator‚Äù spyware by these countries, the PACE mandated "immediately and fully investigate all cases of spyware abuse, punish any findings and provide compensation to victims."
The resolution states that there is sufficient evidence that Azerbaijan used the ‚ÄúPegasus‚Äù spying program in connection with the Armenia-Azerbaijan conflict against a number of people working in Armenia, including an Armenian government official.

As a reminder, in May of this year, the joint investigation of human rights organizations and IT security specialists showed that at least 13 Armenian public figures and officials, including journalists and human rights defenders, became target of the ‚ÄúPegasus‚Äù spy program.
The use of secret spying programs against political opponents, government officials, journalists, human rights defenders and civil society is a violation of the European Convention on Human Rights.
Given the proliferation of such programs, the resolution reaffirms PACE's position that states should use these programs only "in exceptional situations as a last resort" and should avoid exporting these programs to countries where there is a significant risk that they will be used for repression or human rights abuses.

We pray for protection over the innocent people who are caught in the crossfire and the thousands who have lost loved ones in the fighting already. Join us in praying:

"Jesus, you are the Prince of Peace. Bring your peace to your homeland, the land where you paid for sin, conquered death, and won salvation for the world. Somehow, through all of this, use it to make a way for the gospel and bring people to you."

In the midst of the conflict between Israel and Gaza, a troubling pattern emerges. Israel's collective punishment, characterized by cutting off basic human needs, threatens to escalate an already devastating situation. The actions taken have not only deepened the suffering of the population but also raised questions about the proportionality of Israel's retaliation and the rhetoric employed by its government.
